        "$:/language/Help/fetch": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/fetch",
            "description": "Fetch tiddlers from wiki by URL",
            "text": "Fetch one or more files over HTTP/HTTPS, and import the tiddlers matching a filter, optionally transforming the incoming titles.\n\n```\n--fetch file <url> <import-filter> <transform-filter>\n--fetch files <url-filter> <import-filter> <transform-filter>\n--fetch raw-file <url> <transform-filter>\n--fetch raw-files <url-filter> <transform-filter>\n```\n\nThe \"file\" and \"files\" variants fetch the specified files and attempt to import the tiddlers within them (the same processing as if the files were dragged into the browser window). The \"raw-file\" and \"raw-files\" variants fetch the specified files and then store the raw file data in tiddlers, without applying the import logic.\n\nWith the \"file\" and \"raw-file\" variants only a single file is fetched and the first parameter is the URL of the file to read.\n\nWith the \"files\" and \"raw-files\" variants, multiple files are fetched and the first parameter is a filter yielding a list of URLs of the files to read. For example, given a set of tiddlers tagged \"remote-server\" that have a field \"url\" the filter `[tag[remote-server]get[url]]` will retrieve all the available URLs.\n\nFor the \"file\" and \"files\" variants, the `<import-filter>` parameter specifies a filter determining which tiddlers are imported. It defaults to `[all[tiddlers]]` if not provided.\n\nFor all variants, the `<transform-filter>` parameter specifies an optional filter that transforms the titles of the imported tiddlers. For example, `[addprefix[$:/myimports/]]` would add the prefix `$:/myimports/` to each title.\n\nPreceding the `--fetch` command with `--verbose` will output progress information during the import.\n\nNote that TiddlyWiki will not fetch an older version of an already loaded plugin.\n\nThe following example retrieves all the non-system tiddlers from https://tiddlywiki.com and saves them to a JSON file:\n\n```\ntiddlywiki --verbose --fetch file \"https://tiddlywiki.com/\" \"[!is[system]]\" \"\" --rendertiddler \"$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile\" output.json text/plain \"\" exportFilter \"[!is[system]]\"\n```\n\nThe following example retrieves the \"favicon\" file from tiddlywiki.com and saves it in a file called \"output.ico\". Note that the intermediate tiddler \"Icon Tiddler\" is quoted in the \"--fetch\" command because it is being used as a transformation filter to replace the default title, while there are no quotes for the \"--savetiddler\" command because it is being used directly as a title.\n\n```\ntiddlywiki --verbose --fetch raw-file \"https://tiddlywiki.com/favicon.ico\" \"[[Icon Tiddler]]\" --savetiddler \"Icon Tiddler\" output.ico\n```\n\n"
        },

The deserializer must be explicitly specified, unlike the `load` command which infers the deserializer from the file extension.\n\n```\n--import <filepath> <deserializer> [<title>] [<encoding>]\n```\n\nThe deserializers in the core include:\n\n* application/javascript\n* application/json\n* application/x-tiddler\n* application/x-tiddler-html-div\n* application/x-tiddlers\n* text/html\n* text/plain\n\nThe title of the imported tiddler defaults to the filename.\n\nThe encoding defaults to \"utf8\", but can be \"base64\" for importing binary files.\n\nNote that TiddlyWiki will not import an older version of an already loaded plugin.\n"

        "$:/language/Help/listen": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/listen",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki",
            "text": "Serves a wiki over HTTP.\n\nThe listen command uses NamedCommandParameters:\n\n```\n--listen [<name>=<value>]...\n```\n\nAll parameters are optional with safe defaults, and can be specified in any order. The recognised parameters are:\n\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''path-prefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n* ''port'' - port number on which to listen; non-numeric values are interpreted as a system environment variable from which the port number is extracted (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''credentials'' - pathname of credentials CSV file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''anon-username'' - the username for signing edits for anonymous users\n* ''username'' - optional username for basic authentication\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''authenticated-user-header'' - optional name of header to be used for trusted authentication\n* ''readers'' - comma separated list of principals allowed to read from this wiki\n* ''writers'' - comma separated list of principals allowed to write to this wiki\n* ''csrf-disable'' - set to \"yes\" to disable CSRF checks (defaults to \"no\")\n* ''root-tiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''root-render-type'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''root-serve-type'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''tls-cert'' - pathname of TLS certificate file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''tls-key'' - pathname of TLS key file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''debug-level'' - optional debug level; set to \"debug\" to view request details (defaults to \"none\")\n* ''gzip'' - set to \"yes\" to enable gzip compression for some http endpoints (defaults to \"no\")\n\nFor information on opening up your instance to the entire local network, and possible security concerns, see the WebServer tiddler at TiddlyWiki.com.\n\n"
        },

        "$:/language/Help/render": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/render",
            "description": "Renders individual tiddlers to files",
            "text": "Render individual tiddlers identified by a filter and save the results to the specified files.\n\nOptionally, the title of a template tiddler can be specified. In this case, instead of directly rendering each tiddler, the template tiddler is rendered with the \"currentTiddler\" variable set to the title of the tiddler that is being rendered.\n\nA name and value for an additional variable may optionally also be specified.\n\n```\n--render <tiddler-filter> [<filename-filter>] [<render-type>] [<template>] [<name>] [<value>]\n```\n\n* ''tiddler-filter'': A filter identifying the tiddler(s) to be rendered\n* ''filename-filter'': Optional filter transforming tiddler titles into pathnames. If omitted, defaults to `[is[tiddler]addsuffix[.html]]`, which uses the unchanged tiddler title as the filename\n* ''render-type'': Optional render type: `text/html` (the default) returns the full HTML text and `text/plain` just returns the text content (ie it ignores HTML tags and other unprintable material)\n* ''template'': Optional template through which each tiddler is rendered\n* ''name'': Name of optional variable\n* ''value'': Value of optional variable\n\nBy default, the filename is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nNotes:\n\n* The output directory is not cleared of any existing files\n* Any missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n* When referring to a tiddler with spaces in its title, take care to use both the quotes required by your shell and also TiddlyWiki's double square brackets : `--render \"[[Motovun Jack.jpg]]\"`\n* The filename filter is evaluated with the selected items being set to the title of the tiddler currently being rendered, allowing the title to be used as the basis for computing the filename. For example `[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[static/]]` applies URI encoding to each title, and then adds the prefix `static/`\n* The `--render` command is a more flexible replacement for both the `--rendertiddler` and `--rendertiddlers` commands, which are deprecated\n\nExamples:\n\n* `--render \"[!is[system]]\" \"[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[tiddlers/]addsuffix[.html]]\"` -- renders all non-system tiddlers as files in the subdirectory \"tiddlers\" with URL-encoded titles and the extension HTML\n\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/rendertiddler": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/rendertiddler",
            "description": "Render an individual tiddler as a specified ContentType",
            "text": "(Note: The `--rendertiddler` command is deprecated in favour of the new, more flexible `--render` command)\n\nRender an individual tiddler as a specified ContentType, defaulting to `text/html` and save it to the specified filename.\n\nOptionally the title of a template tiddler can be specified, in which case the template tiddler is rendered with the \"currentTiddler\" variable set to the tiddler that is being rendered (the first parameter value).\n\nA name and value for an additional variable may optionally also be specified.\n\n```\n--rendertiddler <title> <filename> [<type>] [<template>] [<name>] [<value>]\n```\n\nBy default, the filename is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nAny missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n\nFor example, the following command saves all tiddlers matching the filter `[tag[done]]` to a JSON file titled `output.json` by employing the core template `$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile`.\n\n```\n--rendertiddler \"$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile\" output.json text/plain \"\" exportFilter \"[tag[done]]\"\n```\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/rendertiddlers": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/rendertiddlers",
            "description": "Render tiddlers matching a filter to a specified ContentType",
            "text": "(Note: The `--rendertiddlers` command is deprecated in favour of the new, more flexible `--render` command)\n\nRender a set of tiddlers matching a filter to separate files of a specified ContentType (defaults to `text/html`) and extension (defaults to `.html`).\n\n```\n--rendertiddlers <filter> <template> <pathname> [<type>] [<extension>] [\"noclean\"]\n```\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--rendertiddlers [!is[system]] $:/core/templates/static.tiddler.html ./static text/plain\n```\n\nBy default, the pathname is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nAny files in the target directory are deleted unless the ''noclean'' flag is specified. The target directory is recursively created if it is missing.\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/save": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/save",
            "description": "Saves individual raw tiddlers to files",
            "text": "Saves individual tiddlers identified by a filter in their raw text or binary format to the specified files.\n\n```\n--save <tiddler-filter> <filename-filter>\n```\n\n* ''tiddler-filter'': A filter identifying the tiddler(s) to be saved\n* ''filename-filter'': Optional filter transforming tiddler titles into pathnames. If omitted, defaults to `[is[tiddler]]`, which uses the unchanged tiddler title as the filename\n\nBy default, the filename is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nNotes:\n\n* The output directory is not cleared of any existing files\n* Any missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n* When saving a tiddler with spaces in its title, take care to use both the quotes required by your shell and also TiddlyWiki's double square brackets : `--save \"[[Motovun Jack.jpg]]\"`\n* The filename filter is evaluated with the selected items being set to the title of the tiddler currently being saved, allowing the title to be used as the basis for computing the filename. For example `[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[static/]]` applies URI encoding to each title, and then adds the prefix `static/`\n* The `--save` command is a more flexible replacement for both the `--savetiddler` and `--savetiddlers` commands, which are deprecated\n\nExamples:\n\n* `--save \"[!is[system]is[image]]\" \"[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[tiddlers/]]\"` -- saves all non-system image tiddlers as files in the subdirectory \"tiddlers\" with URL-encoded titles\n"
        },

        "$:/language/Help/savewikifolder": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/savewikifolder",
            "description": "Saves a wiki to a new wiki folder",
            "text": "<<.from-version \"5.1.20\">> Saves the current wiki as a wiki folder, including tiddlers, plugins and configuration:\n\n```\n--savewikifolder <wikifolderpath> [<filter>]\n```\n\n* The target wiki folder must be empty or non-existent\n* The filter specifies which tiddlers should be included. It is optional, defaulting to `[all[tiddlers]]`\n* Plugins from the official plugin library are replaced with references to those plugins in the `tiddlywiki.info` file\n* Custom plugins are unpacked into their own folder\n\nA common usage is to convert a TiddlyWiki HTML file into a wiki folder:\n\n```\ntiddlywiki --load ./mywiki.html --savewikifolder ./mywikifolder\n```\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/server": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/server",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki (deprecated in favour of the new listen command)",
            "text": "Legacy command to serve a wiki over HTTP.\n\n```\n--server <port> <root-tiddler> <root-render-type> <root-serve-type> <username> <password> <host> <path-prefix> <debug-level>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''port'' - port number on which to listen; non-numeric values are interpreted as a system environment variable from which the port number is extracted (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''root-tiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''root-render-type'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''root-serve-type'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''username'' - the default username for signing edits\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''path-prefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n* ''debug-level'' - optional debug level; set to \"debug\" to view request details (defaults to \"none\")\n\nIf the password parameter is specified then the browser will prompt the user for the username and password. Note that the password is transmitted in plain text so this implementation should only be used on a trusted network or over HTTPS.\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n\nThe username and password can be specified as empty strings if you need to set the hostname or pathprefix and don't want to require a password.\n\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html \"\" \"\" 192.168.0.245\n```\n\nUsing an address like this exposes your system to the local network. For information on opening up your instance to the entire local network, and possible security concerns, see the WebServer tiddler at TiddlyWiki.com.\n\nTo run multiple TiddlyWiki servers at the same time you'll need to put each one on a different port. It can be useful to use an environment variable to pass the port number to the Node.js process. This example references an environment variable called \"MY_PORT_NUMBER\":\n\n```\n--server MY_PORT_NUMBER $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n"
        },

Address box sizing set to `content-box` in IE 8/9/10.\n * 2. Remove excess padding in IE 8/9/10.\n */\n\ninput[type=\"checkbox\"],\ninput[type=\"radio\"] {\n  box-sizing: border-box; /* 1 */\n  padding: 0; /* 2 */\n}\n\n/**\n * Fix the cursor style for Chrome's increment/decrement buttons. For certain\n * `font-size` values of the `input`, it causes the cursor style of the\n * decrement button to change from `default` to `text`.\n */\n\ninput[type=\"number\"]::-webkit-inner-spin-button,\ninput[type=\"number\"]::-webkit-outer-spin-button {\n  height: auto;\n}\n\n/**\n * 1. Correct `color` not being inherited in IE 8/9.\n * 2. Remove padding so people aren't caught out if they zero out fieldsets.\n */\n\nlegend {\n  border: 0; /* 1 */\n  padding: 0; /* 2 */\n}\n\n/**\n * Remove default vertical scrollbar in IE 8/9.\n */\n\ntextarea {\n  overflow: auto;\n}\n\n/**\n * Don't inherit the `font-weight` (applied by a rule above).\n * NOTE: the default cannot safely be changed in Chrome and Safari on OS X.\n */\n\noptgroup {\n  font-weight: bold;\n}\n\n/* Tables\n   ========================================================================== */\n\n/**\n * Remove most spacing between table cells.\n */\n\ntable {\n  border-collapse: collapse;\n  border-spacing: 0;\n}\n\ntd,\nth {\n  padding: 0;\n}\n"
        },
        "$:/themes/tiddlywiki/vanilla/settings/fontfamily": {

"""
Airflow is implemented via [[Jarvis]].
Airflow is a DAG orchestration tool.
DAG is a way to connect different task together

DAG is setup via a config file. Config files are deployed to an Airflow cluster which runs the DAG
Each node of DAG is a task in AirFlow. 
Airflow is not distributed.

Jarvis file structure contains a Customer directory and each client will have a sub-directory within that.
There is a configs sub-directory for each customer with their specific config json files. These config files contains the step information (pre-processor, records parser, record eval...)

Each step can contain push and pull (xcom_push_variable, xcom_pull_variable) variables. These allow information to be passed to and from different steps (as normally they are self contained and don't "talk" to each other)

There are different types of jobs in the config file (HTTP and SPARK). There is no push variable for SPARK.

Each client has their own Python file, which can be considered the MAIN class for the customer. Airflow calls this python file. DAGS are defined in this Python file.

GCP directory structure
"""

* Bucket
**Specific Bucket
***dags directory
****jarvis directory
*****base directory
******jarvis python file (utility functions)
*****customer directory
******//customer name// directory
*******python files
*******configs directory

"""
Incoming file monitoring will be handled either by AirFlow Sensors or GlobalScape tool
The AirFlow Sensors can trigger DAGs to run.

*run QPST

When running request via Postman for Habu testing, one of the response errors I got was 

```
Required request body is missing: public org.springframework.http.ResponseEntity<com.habu.api.external.controller.v1.model.CleanRoomUser> com.habu.api.external.http.controller.cleanroom.CleanRoomController.addCleanroomUser(java.lang.String,com.habu.api.external.controller.v1.model.AddCleanRoomUserRequest)
```

I'd put the required parameters in the parameter tab, but ChatGPT noted that this message usually meant that the API was expecting a JSON body, which my request was not providing. I disabled my parameters in that tab and entered them in JSON format in the Body tab instead. This got rid of that error.

"""
(The following applies to KBM implementation of their automation process)

Automation project is a Maven project
You can use a maven project to import jar files needed for dependencies

Update the ''pom.xml'' file with dependencies, which can be found: https://mvnrepository.com/

''Feature files'' (cucumber format files; Given/When/Then)
These are broken down by Feed (one feature file for a given feed)
``root/src/test/resources/FeatureFiles/<client>/``

''Step definitions'' (the code that the cucumber feature files are calling)
``root/src/test/java/com.kbm.test.step.definitions/``

''Step runner'' files bind the Feature file to the Step definitions file.
``root/src/test/java/com.kbm.test.runner.<client>``

Contains @CucumberOptions for:
	feature file name and location
	Plugins needed
	"glue", which is the sep definitions directory
	tags

Performs environment initialization (pulls data from the configuration information found in (``root/src/main/resources/``)
Also contains element at the very end for stack tracing hooks in order to document all information introduced by the test run so it can be backed out and the same data can be re-used.
(Records can't be removed from Kafka or Hive though)

''WTEUtils.java'' file contains framework for basic creation of files, reading from excel, setting delimiters...

''TestNG'' Test (Run As account)
(Needed to manually install it using http://dl.bintray.com/testng-team/testng-eclipse-release/ as the URL


Test data files (``root/src/resources/TestFile/<client>/``) contain several tabs (generally)
Feed Config tab - contains things like client, environment, template name and pattern, groupID(EFID), Load Strategy (InsertUpdate...), delimiter, header flag, file extension, entity name and primary key
tabs for each area where a validation will occur (Raw file, customDB, hiveDB, fatalFile, uniMart)
On these validation tabs, there will be a column for the test scenario description, Ingestion Count (i.e. the run number) and designated fields and their corresponding values.
hiveDB will also have an additional column to cover the expected action flag values (I, U, D)


Configuration information found in ``root/src/main/resources/``
contains server information (hive, postgres, oracle...); schema values, FTP directories, hive schemas, unimart schema...
Also contains accounts to use for connection







Below is example from Udemy Learn Selenium Java Cucumber course. Simple way to create a web driver instance, command a browser to open and check an element value on a page




```
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;

/*
Test case
-------
1) Launch browser (chrome)
2) Open URL  https://demo.opencart.com/
3) Validate title should be   "Your Store"
4) close browser
*/

public class FirstTestCase {

	public static void main(String[] args) {

		// 1) Launch browser (chrome)

		// ChromeDriver driver = new ChromeDriver(); //starts a new constructor
		WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver(); // Alternate way; Upcasting

		// 2) Open URL https://www.idpa.com/

		driver.get("https://www.idpa.com/");

		// 3) Validate title should be "International Defensive Pistol Association"

		String actual_title = driver.getTitle();

		if (actual_title.equals("International Defensive Pistol Association")) {
			System.out.println("Test Passed");
		} else {
			System.out.println("Test Failed");
		}

		// 4) close browser
		driver.close();
		// driver.quit(); //this will work too

	}

}
```













touch - creates file if doesn't exist; if exists, changes the update timestamp.

To run a script, type

```
>bash hello.sh
```


bash is needed because files, by default are not executable and need bash to execute
To make a file executable, use chmod.

```
chmod 755 hello.sh
```


Once done, to run the file without using the bash prefix, you must preface the file name with ./  The ./ is needed because the system searches the PATH for the way to execute something. The ./ notes to not check the PATH

```
>./hello.sh
```


Comments start with #

Parameters
$0 is usually the name of the script, the path included
Then Parameters increment ($1, $2...)

To check the last exit code value, type

```
>echo $?
```

```
if [ -z $DELAY ]
then
  echo "You must supply a delay"
  exit 1
fi
```

"""
To see the records that are returned by find, replace -delete with -print


Use the Unix find command to search for files
To use theÂ ''findÂ ''command, at theÂ UnixÂ prompt, enter:
"""

```
 find . -name "pattern" -print
```
"""
ReplaceÂ "pattern"Â with a filename or matching expression, such asÂ "*.txt". (Leave the double quotes in.)
Options
The general form of the command is:
"""

```
 find (starting directory) (matching criteria and actions)
```
"""
TheÂ findÂ command will begin looking in the starting directory you specify and proceed to search through all accessible subdirectories. You may specify more than one starting directory for searching.
You have several options for matching criteria:
"""

|-atime n|	File was accessedÂ nÂ days ago|
|-mtime n|File was modifiedÂ nÂ days ago|
|-size n|File isÂ nÂ blocks big (a block is 512 bytes)|
|-type c|Specifies file type: f=plain text, d=directory|
|-fstype typ|Specifies file system type: 4.2 or nfs|
|-name nam|The filename isÂ nam|
|-user usr|The file's owner isÂ usr|
|-group grp|The file's group owner isÂ grp|
|-perm p|The file's access mode isÂ pÂ (whereÂ pÂ is an integer)|
"""
You can useÂ +Â (plus) andÂ -Â (minus) modifiers with theÂ atime,Â mtime, andÂ sizeÂ criteria to increase their usefulness, for example:
"""

|-mtime +7|Matches files modified more than seven days ago|
|-atime -2|Matches files accessed less than two days ago|
|-size +100|Matches files larger than 100 blocks (50KB)|
"""
By default, multiple options are joined by "and". You may specify "or" with theÂ -oÂ flag and the use of grouped parentheses. To match all files modified more than 7 days ago and accessed more than 30 days ago, use:
 \( -mtime +7 -atime +30 \)
To match all files modified more than 7 days ago or accessed more than 30 days ago, use:
 \( -mtime +7 -o -atime +30 \)
You may specify "not" with an exclamation point. To match all files ending inÂ .txtÂ except the fileÂ notme.txt, use:
 \! -name notme.txt -name \*.txt
You can specify the following actions for the list of files that theÂ findÂ command locates:
"""

|-print|Display pathnames of matching files.|
|-exec cmd|Execute commandÂ cmdÂ on a file.|
|-ok cmd|Prompt before executing the commandÂ cmdÂ on a file.|
|-mount|(System V) Restrict to file system of starting directory.|
|-xdev|(BSD) Restrict to file system of starting directory.|
|-prune|(BSD) Don't descend into subdirectories.|
"""
Executed commands must end withÂ \;Â (a backslash and semi-colon) and may useÂ {}Â (curly braces) as a placeholder for each file that theÂ findÂ command locates. For example, for a long listing of each file found, use:
 -exec ls -l {} \;
Matching criteria and actions may appear in any order and are evaluated from left to right.
Full examples
	â€¢ To find and report allÂ CÂ language source code files starting at the current directory, enter:
 find . -name \*.c -print
	â€¢ To report all files starting in the directoriesÂ /mydir1Â andÂ /mydir2Â larger than 2,000 blocks (about 1,000KB) and that have not been accessed in over 30 days, enter:
 find /mydir1 /mydir2 -size +2000 -atime +30 -print
	â€¢ To remove (with prompting) all files starting in theÂ /mydirÂ directory that have not been accessed in over 100 days, enter:
 find /mydir -atime +100 -ok rm {} \;
	â€¢ To show a long listing starting inÂ /mydirÂ of files not modified in over 20 days or not accessed in over 40 days, enter:
 find /mydir \(-mtime +20 -o -atime +40\) -exec ls -l {} \;
	â€¢ To list and remove all regular files namedÂ coreÂ starting in the directoryÂ /progÂ that are larger than 500KB, enter:
 find /prog -type f -size +1000 -print -name core -exec rm {} \;
Note:
On some systems, the name of the starting directory must end with aÂ /Â (slash), or theÂ findÂ command will return nothing. Thus, the starting directory in the previous example would be designated asÂ /prog/, with a trailing slash. On other systems, a trailing slash does not affect the command. A trailing slash is never needed when searching inÂ /Â (the root directory),Â .Â (the current directory), orÂ ..Â (the parent directory).

```
 \( -mtime +7 -o -atime +30 \)
```

You may specify "not" with an exclamation point. To match all files ending inÂ .txtÂ except the fileÂ notme.txt, use:

```
 \! -name notme.txt -name \*.txt
```
"""
You can specify the following actions for the list of files that theÂ ''findÂ ''command locates:
"""

|-print|Display pathnames of matching files.|
|-exec cmd|Execute commandÂ cmdÂ on a file.|
|-ok cmd|Prompt before executing the commandÂ cmdÂ on a file.|
|-mount|(System V) Restrict to file system of starting directory.|
|-xdev|(BSD) Restrict to file system of starting directory.|
|-prune|(BSD) Don't descend into subdirectories.|
"""
Executed commands must end withÂ ''\;''Â (a backslash and semi-colon) and may useÂ {}Â (curly braces) as a placeholder for each file that theÂ findÂ command locates. For example, for a long listing of each file found, use:
"""

```
 -exec ls -l {} \;
```

"""
Matching criteria and actions may appear in any order and are evaluated from left to right.

''Full examples''
	â€¢ To find and report allÂ CÂ language source code files starting at the current directory, enter:
"""

```
 find . -name \*.c -print
```

	â€¢ To report all files starting in the directoriesÂ /mydir1Â andÂ /mydir2Â larger than 2,000 blocks (about 1,000KB) and that have not been accessed in over 30 days, enter:

```
 find /mydir1 /mydir2 -size +2000 -atime +30 -print
```

	â€¢ To remove (with prompting) all files starting in theÂ /mydirÂ directory that have not been accessed in over 100 days, enter:

```
 find /mydir -atime +100 -ok rm {} \;
```

	â€¢ To show a long listing starting inÂ /mydirÂ of files not modified in over 20 days or not accessed in over 40 days, enter:

```
 find /mydir \(-mtime +20 -o -atime +40\) -exec ls -l {} \;
```

	â€¢ To list and remove all regular files namedÂ coreÂ starting in the directoryÂ /progÂ that are larger than 500KB, enter:

```
 find /prog -type f -size +1000 -print -name core -exec rm {} \;
```

Note:
On some systems, the name of the starting directory must end with aÂ /Â (slash), or theÂ findÂ command will return nothing. Thus, the starting directory in the previous example would be designated asÂ /prog/, with a trailing slash. On other systems, a trailing slash does not affect the command. A trailing slash is never needed when searching inÂ /Â (the root directory),Â .Â (the current directory), orÂ ..Â (the parent directory).

The below will list each of the sub-directories one level down from /var and then end with the total of all.
Sudo is not necessary though.

```
sudo du -shc /var/*
```

An alternative is to use --max-depth to list how many levels to go down.


```
sudo du -h --max-depth=1 /var
```

To list only the 5 largest directories, use the pipe and sort. The below would return the top 5 directories sorted from largest.


```
sudo du -h /var/ | sort -rh | head -5
```

"""
Output to file uses the greater than signs (`>` and `>>`) to denote the file name (or name and path) to write the output.
The single greater than will overwrite any existing data in the target file
The double greater than will append data to the existing file
"""






"""
To make a shell script executable from just about anywhere, create a /bin directory in your home (~) directory.
Then place any shell scripts there.
That is you local PATH so entering the shell script name anywhere will point to that script.
"""






"""The below script was written by Ram. To run it, enter the script name and follow it by the HIVE schema you want to check the table on.  This will return the "show create table" output for each and save it to a file. 
Afterwards, open the output file and check for instance of "avro". There should be very few.

"""

```
###########################################################################################################################
# Author Ram Pawar                                                                                                        #
#                                                                                                                         #
# Objective of this shell script is to capture all the tables in a schema and capture all DDL statements                  #
#                                                                                                                         #
# Parameters : Command line 1 - Provide the schema name                                                                   #     
# Output : Creates an output file with {schema name}__DDL_statements.txt                                                  #
#                                                                                                                         #
#                                                                                                                         #
##########################################################################################################################
#!/bin/bash

######## - declarations 

hiveDBName="$1"
terminate=";"
showcreate="show create table "

tables=`hive -e "use $hiveDBName;show tables;"`

tab_list=`echo "${tables}"`

for list in $tab_list
do

showcreatetable=${showcreatetable}${showcreate}${list}${terminate}

done

rm -f ${hiveDBName}_tempCommands.txt

echo ${showcreatetable} >> ${hiveDBName}_tempCommands.txt

sed -i 's/show\screate\stable\stab_name;//g' ${hiveDBName}_tempCommands.txt
sed -i 's/show\screate\stable\s+-*+;//g' ${hiveDBName}_tempCommands.txt
sed -i 's/show\screate\stable\s|;//g' ${hiveDBName}_tempCommands.txt

showcreatetable=""

showcreatetable=`cat  ${hiveDBName}_tempCommands.txt`

echo "~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ UPDATED ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ " ${showcreatetable}

rm -f ${hiveDBName}_DDL_statements.txt
hive -e "use $hiveDBName; ${showcreatetable}" >> ${hiveDBName}_DDL_statements.txt


```







Read from text example:

```
COUNT=1

# IFS is the internal field separator tells the system how to parses lines read in; It is blank below because what is being read in doesn't need to be parsed
# -r denotes to not allow backslashes to be used for escape
# LINE is the variable to hold the current line of text

while IFS='' read -r LINE
do
  echo "LINE $COUNT: $LINE"
  ((COUNT++))

# In < "$1"  The $1 is the first parameter passed to the script (as usual). The less than sign says use redirection so that we can use the past file as input.

done < "$1"
```








"""The below is meant to run agains the /etc/passwd file as an argument because that file has a set format;
The first line is doing the usual read command but afterwards it's listing the fields expected on each line with their position.
The echo is only returning the values in the designated positions (user, home and shell).
"""


```
while IFS=: read -r user pass uid gid gecos home shell; do
  echo "$user $home $shell"
done < "$1"
```

To run an entire script in debugger mode, add a -x after Bash; debugger lines are preceded by + in the output

```
>bash -x script.sh
```


If you want to run just a portion of a script under debugger, place set -x at the beginning of the code and set +x at the end.
Ex

```
#!/usr/bin/env/ bash
set -x
for i in {1..10} ;do
  echo $1
done
set +x
```


It is also possible to output to the console without the debugger information but have the debugger info output to a file.
Ex

```
>script.sh 2> debug.text
```

"""
Per this class, all variables should be double-quoted.
''"$0"'' is a variable that hold the Shell or the path to the script being run
''"$1"'' is the first variable passed to a command ($2 is the 2nd, $3 the third...)
''"$@"'' will be a list of all variables (arguments) passed; this will keep space information and break up values. So if there were 3 variables passed, this command would return 3 separate values
''"$*"'' is similar to $@ in that is holds a list of all variables. However, it keeps them all as one text string. So if the same 3 variables are passed it would only return one variable but a string of all 3 together.
"""

https://developers.google.com/display-video/api/structured-data-file/v5-5/LineItem

```
List of IDs, where each daypart ID is constructed in the following format:
daypart_id = base_dayparting_id
+ days_since_monday * 10000
+ start * 100
+ end

base_dayparting_id = 300000
days_since_monday: 0=Monday, 1=Tuesday, ..., 6=Sunday
start: 0..95 (00:00--23:45) an integer from 0-95, representing 15min slots
end: 1..96 (00:15--24:00); an integer from 0-95, representing 15min slots
start < end
For new entities, times will be set in the timezone of your users (i.e., "Local"). For existing entities, the timezone will not be changed.
```


For example, a daypart id = 367296

*Ignore the leading 3.
*Day is 2nd digit, 6, so this would be Sundays
*Beginning time is the next two digits (72).  That's 72 blocks of 15 minutes. So multiply by 15 to get the number of minutes and then divide by 60 to get the number of hours (18).
*End time is the last two digits (96). Using the same calculation, that returns 24 (so end of the day)

You can encode a SHA1 hash using various programming languages and tools. Here are a few methods:

!Python

```
import hashlib

# Define the value to be encoded
value = "Hello, World!"

# Create a SHA1 hash object
sha1_hash = hashlib.sha1()

# Update the hash object with the bytes of the value
sha1_hash.update(value.encode('utf-8'))

# Get the hexadecimal representation of the hash
hashed_value = sha1_hash.hexdigest()

print(f"The SHA1 hash of '{value}' is: {hashed_value}")
```



! JavaScript
Using the `crypto` module (Node.js):

```javascript
const crypto = require('crypto');

const value = "Hello, World!";
const sha1Hash = crypto.createHash('sha1').update(value).digest('hex');

console.log(`The SHA1 hash of '${value}' is: ${sha1Hash}`);
```

! Java
Using the `MessageDigest` class:

```java
import java.security.MessageDigest;
import java.security.NoSuchAlgorithmException;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws NoSuchAlgorithmException {
        String value = "Hello, World!";
        MessageDigest md = MessageDigest.getInstance("SHA-1");
        byte[] hashBytes = md.digest(value.getBytes());
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        for (byte b : hashBytes) {
            sb.append(String.format("%02x", b));
        }
        System.out.println("The SHA1 hash of '" + value + "' is: " + sb.toString());
    }
}
```

! C#
Using the `SHA1` class from `System.Security.Cryptography`:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Security.Cryptography;
using System.Text;

class Program {
    static void Main() {
        string value = "Hello, World!";
        using (SHA1 sha1 = SHA1.Create()) {
            byte[] hashBytes = sha1.ComputeHash(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(value));
            StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
            foreach (byte b in hashBytes) {
                sb.Append(b.ToString("x2"));
            }
            Console.WriteLine($"The SHA1 hash of '{value}' is: {sb.ToString()}");
        }
    }
}
```

! PHP
Using the `hash` function:

```php
$value = "Hello, World!";
$sha1Hash = hash('sha1', $value);

echo "The SHA1 hash of '{$value}' is: {$sha1Hash}\n";
```

! Bash
Using `openssl` command:

```bash
value="Hello, World!"
sha1_hash=$(echo -n "$value" | openssl dgst -sha1)
echo "The SHA1 hash of '$value' is: $sha1_hash"
```

These examples show how to generate SHA1 hashes using different programming languages and tools. Each method provides a way to achieve the same result, allowing you to choose the best fit for your specific environment or application.

```
Sub CSVFile()
Dim SrcRg As Range
Dim CurrRow As Range
Dim CurrCell As Range
Dim CurrTextStr As String
Dim ListSep As String
Dim FName As Variant
FName = Application.GetSaveAsFilename("", "CSV File (*.csv), *.csv")
ListSep = Application.International(xlListSeparator)
  If Selection.Cells.Count > 1 Then
    Set SrcRg = Selection
  Else
    Set SrcRg = ActiveSheet.UsedRange
  End If
Open FName For Output As #1
For Each CurrRow In SrcRg.Rows
  CurrTextStr = Ã¬Ã®
For Each CurrCell In CurrRow.Cells
  CurrTextStr = CurrTextStr & """" & CurrCell.Value & """" & ListSep
Next
While Right(CurrTextStr, 1) = ListSep
  CurrTextStr = Left(CurrTextStr, Len(CurrTextStr) - 1)
Wend
Print #1, CurrTextStr
Next
Close #1
End Sub
```

```
Sub FixedLength()
Dim delimiter As String
Dim quotes As Integer
Dim Returned As String
delimiter = " "
quotes = MsgBox("Surround Cell Information with Quotes?", vbYesNo)
' Call the WriteFile function passing the delimiter and quotes options.
Returned = WriteFile(delimiter, quotes)
' Print a message box indicating if the process was completed.
Select Case Returned
Case "Canceled"
MsgBox "The export operation was canceled."
Case "Exported"
MsgBox "The information was exported."
End Select
End Sub
'- â€”
Function WriteFile(delimiter As String, quotes As Integer) As String
' Dimension variables to be used in this function.
Dim CurFile As String
Dim SaveFileName
Dim CellText As String
Dim RowNum As Integer
Dim ColNum As Integer
Dim FNum As Integer
Dim TotalRows As Double
Dim TotalCols As Double
' Show Save As dialog box with the .TXT file name as the default.
' Test to see what kind of system this macro is being run on.
If Left(Application.OperatingSystem, 3) = "Win" Then
SaveFileName = Application.GetSaveAsFilename(CurFile, _
"Text Delimited (*.txt), *.txt", , "Text Delimited Exporter")
Else
SaveFileName = Application.GetSaveAsFilename(CurFile, _
"TEXT", , "Text Delimited Exporter")
End If
' Check to see if Cancel was clicked.
If SaveFileName = False Then
WriteFile = "Canceled"
Exit Function
End If
' Obtain the next free file number.
FNum = FreeFile()
' Open the selected file name for data output.
Open SaveFileName For Output As #FNum
' Store the total number of rows and columns to variables.
TotalRows = Selection.Rows.Count
TotalCols = Selection.Columns.Count
' Loop through every cell, from left to right and top to bottom.
For RowNum = 1 To TotalRows
For ColNum = 1 To TotalCols
With Selection.Cells(RowNum, ColNum)
Dim ColWidth As Integer
ColWidth = Application.RoundUp(.ColumnWidth, 0)
' Store the current cells contents to a variable.
Select Case .HorizontalAlignment
Case xlRight
CellText = Space(Abs(ColWidth - Len(.Text))) & .Text
Case xlCenter
CellText = Space(Abs(ColWidth - Len(.Text)) / 2) & .Text & _
Space(Abs(ColWidth - Len(.Text)) / 2)
Case Else
CellText = .Text & Space(Abs(ColWidth - Len(.Text)))
End Select
End With
' Write the contents to the file.
' With or without quotation marks around the cell information.
Select Case quotes
Case vbYes
CellText = Chr(34) & CellText & Chr(34)
Case vbNo
CellText = CellText
End Select
Print #FNum, CellText;
' Update the status bar with the progress.
Application.StatusBar = Format((((RowNum - 1) * TotalCols) _
+ ColNum) / (TotalRows * TotalCols), "0%") & " Completed."
' Loop to the next column.
Next ColNum
' Add a linefeed character at the end of each row.
If RowNum <> TotalRows Then Print #FNum, ""
' Loop to the next row.
Next RowNum
' Close the .prn file.
Close #FNum
' Reset the status bar.
Application.StatusBar = False
WriteFile = "Exported"
End Function
```








Instead of nested IF statements, use the IFS function.


```
=IFS([Something is True1, Value if True1,Something is True2,Value if True2,Something is True3,Value if True3)
```


Example would be if another field (E6) is 1 then populate with 3, if 2 then 4....

```
=IFS(E6=1,3,E6=2,4,E6=3,1,E6=4,2)
```







The LOOKUP function has issues with certain types of data. Instead use INDEXT/MATCH combination.
Â 
Example:

```
=IFERROR(INDEX(C:C,MATCH(D4,A:A,0)),"")
```

Â 
The MATCH portion above searches for value D4 in A column. If it finds a match then it will return the row number.
The INDEX portion looks in the C column and returns whatever is in the row specified (i.e. what the MATCH returned).
I added the IFERROR so you wouldnâ€™t get a #N/A if there was no match.







```
MID(text, start_num, num_chars)
```

Finds strings within a string. Useful for checking mappings on OUT/FLT records for fixed width files.






"""This was created based upon name values found the an list of AMLK_PII records. The name was all on the same line in Fname Mname Lname and I needed to put each into its separate field.

The full name was pasted in column D
Formula in column G for the first name is: 
"""

```
=TRIM(LEFT(RIGHT(A19,LEN(A19)-FIND(",",A19,1)-1),IFERROR(FIND(" ",RIGHT(A19,LEN(A19)-FIND(",",A19,1)-1)),LEN(RIGHT(A19,LEN(A19)-FIND(",",A19,1)-1)))))
```

```
=TRIM(IF(LEFT(RIGHT(D49,2),1) = " ",RIGHT(D49,1),""))
```

Column I for the last name is

```
=TRIM(LEFT(A19,FIND(",",A19,1)-1))
```

http://stackoverflow.com/questions/9122046/getting-formula-of-another-cell-in-target-cell

1) Going to Formulas -> Define Name, I defined two named ranges (see fig. 
2), with the information shown in cells A6:B8.
Enter in cell B2 =FormulaAsText. This will retrieve the formula in cell A2 as text.

Explanation: The named range FormulaAsText uses =GET.CELL(info_type,reference). In this case, Ã¬nfo_type = 6 retrieves the formula, and reference = OFFSET(INDIRECT("RC",FALSE),0,-1) uses the cell with 0 rows and -1 columns offset from the one the formula is used in.

Copy B2 and paste into B3:B4. This will show formulas in A3:A4. Cell A4 shows that the worksheet function CELL only retrieves values, not formulas (as opposed to GET.CELL).

Since FormulaAsText gets the formula from a cell at fixed offset (0,-1) from the current, I defined another range FormulaAsText2, which uses an offset (rows,cols) read from the worksheet itself. Cells D2:D4 contain =FormulaAsText2. Thus, cell D2 shows the contents of cell B3 (=OffSET(D2,1,-2)), which is FormulaAsText. cells D3:D4 show the contents of themselves. This adds some flexibility. YMMV.






TRIM is used to get rid of spaces. If you want to trim a value down then use a combination of LEFT, LEN (and maybe RIGHT).

For example to get rid of a comma at the end of a value and the spaces, I used something like:

```
=LEFT(TRIM(N5), LEN(N5)-1)
```

Or if you don't need to trim spaces and just clip off the last character:

```
=LEFT(N5, LEN(N5)-1)
```

Normally when editing a python script while working with a Flask project, you'd have to save you changes and refresh the web page in order to see those changes. Denoting that you're in Debug mode will allow changes to be automatically saved and applied to the site.

Just add (debug=True) to the `if __name__` portion at the bottom of the python script.

```
if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(debug=True)
```







In the below example, there is a Login page with a form that has a text box to enter a name and a Submit button. Entering a name and pressing Submit will sent a POST. The code on the python file will redirect the user to a specific page for them if the Submit button is selected. Otherwise, if you go to the login page it will just display the entry form.

Primary python file. The /login section shows POSTing entered data in the /login page.


```
from flask import Flask, redirect, url_for, render_template, request

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route("/")
def home():
    qa_staff = ['Tim', 'Ana', 'Bob', 'Matt']
    staff_size = len(qa_staff)
    return render_template("index.html", content="String from main python file", staff = qa_staff, size = staff_size)

@app.route("/login", methods = ["POST", "GET"])
def login():
    #if the person hits the Submit button (so it's a POST request), then it will take them to the custom page for the name they entrered to submit
    if request.method == 'POST':
        user = request.form['nm']
        return redirect(url_for('user', usr=user))
    #Otherwise it will just go to the default login page.
    else:
        return render_template("login.html")

@app.route("/<usr>")
def user(usr):
    return f"<h1>{usr}</h1>"

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)
```

login.html, which uses a form to process entered name information. The POST occurs when the Submit button is pressed.


```
{% extends "base.html" %}
{% block title %}Login Page{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
<form action="#" method="post">
  <p>Name: </p>
  <p><input type="text" name="nm" /></p>
  <p><input type="submit" value="submit" /></p>
</form>
{% endblock%}
```







```
from flask import Flask, redirect, url_for

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route("/")
def index():
    return "Test flask implementation"

@app.route("/home")
def home():
    return "This is the home page <h1>HELLO!</h1>"
```

Pass ''parameters ''to the page:

```
#Add parameter in <> to pass to function
@app.route("/<name>")
def user(name):
    return f"Hello {name}"
```

''Redirect ''to different page:


```
#Redirect to a different page, using redirect and url_for
#Will redirect people to the /<name> page.
#You can pass along an argument (name = ) with the url redirect.
@app.route("/admin/") #Adding a slash after the name allows for the user to use the slash or not in the actual URL (
def admin():
    #the "user" below is calling the function user, under the @app.route("/<name>")
    return redirect(url_for("user", name = 'Admin'))
```

''Include this at the bottom'' of the code

```
if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(host="0.0.0.0", port=5000)
```

Within the text of a tiddler you can use special formatting called WikiText to control how the text is displayed.

WikiText can be typed by using the [[Editor toolbar]] or by typing by hand. While the first is convenient the later can be faster when you know the WikiText markup code.

! Simple Formatting

At its simplest, WikiText lets you use familiar word-processing features like bold, italic, lists and tables. For example:

```
The ''quick'' brown ~~flea~~ fox //jumps// over the `lazy` dog
```

â€¦ displays as:

The ''quick'' brown ~~flea~~ fox //jumps// over the `lazy` dog

! Working with Tiddlers

In WikiText, you can link to tiddlers using double square brackets, or by taking advantage of the automatic linking of CamelCase words:

```
This is a link to HelloThere, and one to [[History of TiddlyWiki]]
```

â€¦ displays as:

This is a link to HelloThere, and one to [[History of TiddlyWiki]]

To suppress a ~CamelCase tiddler link, preface the ~ character before the text to be suppressed.

! Macros

Macros let you package repetitive fragments of WikiText so that you can easily reuse them.

For example, here is the definition of a macro that generates a ~YouTube video URL from its unique identifier:

```
\define youtube(video)
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=$video$
\end
```

With that definition in place, `<<youtube 1g66s7UbyuU>>` generates the URL https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1g66s7UbyuU

! Advanced WikiText

Advanced WikiText features allow you to produce automated lists and interactive features like dropdown menus. In fact, the entire user interface of TiddlyWiki itself is written in WikiText, so any feature that you see in TiddlyWiki can be adapted for use in your own wikis.

Some of the advanced features require complex coding. TiddlyWiki includes several built-in macros that simplify common user interface tasks, like tabs, tables of content, and lists of tiddlers.

! Find out more

See [[WikiText]] for a detailed introduction to writing WikiText.

*Numeric Data
**Integer (int64)
***Whole numbers that can be negative (-2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3...)
**Float (float64)
***1.000000001

*String Data
**Strings
***Text values ('dog', 'cat','800-999-9999')
**In SQL, use single quotes when dealing with strings like 'Google Inc.'
**String Functions
***`CONCAT("12345","678")` : "12345678"
***`ENDS_WITH("Apple", "e")` : TRUE
***`LOWER("Apple")` : "apple"
***`REGEXP_CONTAINS("Lunchbox", r"^*box$")` : TRUE

*Dates
**Dates (datetime)
***Stored in universal time format. Allowable range: 0001-01-01 00:00:00 to 9999-12-31 23:59:59.999999
***YYYY-MM-DD is expected format for dates
**Date Functions
***`CURRENT_DATE([time_zone)]` : Today's Date
***`EXTRACT(year FROM your_date_field)` : Year of date (try changing Year to Month, Day, Week...)
***`DATE_ADD(DATE "2008-12-25",INTERVAL 5 DAY)` : Adds an interval of time
***`SELECT DATE_SUB(DATE "2008-12-25", INTERVAL 5 DAY)` : Subtracts an interval of time
***`DATE_DIFF(DATE "2010-07-07", DATE "2008-12-25")` : Subtracts two dates and returns interval
***`DATE_TRUNC(DATE "2008-12-25", MONTH)` : Truncates the date (e.g. 2008-12-01)
***`FORMAT_DATETIME()` : Formats an existing date to a different date string format
***`PARSE_DATETIME()` : Example: Turn "12/01/2017" to a proper date "2017-12-01"

*Other
**`Boolean (Y/N)`
**`Array ['apple','pear']`
**`Struct <apple string>`

*`SELECT CAST("12345" AS INT64)`

**2017-08-01

**"1112223333"
*`SELECT SAFE_CAST("apple" AS INT64)`
**NULL

Big Query can directly query data files that live in Google Cloud Storage. This is creating an â€œexternalâ€ data source connection (Federated SQL Query).

Demo example:
Cloud Storage contains many Parquet files. This data needs to be queried from Big Query.

*Step 1: Create a table definition file.
**`bq mkdef --source_format PARQUET --hive_partitioning_mode=AUTO --hive_partitioning_source_uri_prefix=gs://fh-arc/ gs://fh-commoncrawl/cc-index/table/cc/main/warc/* > /tmp/common_crawl_tabledef`
**Above comment denotes the underlying data is in PARQUET format; the data is high partitioned; we are requesting automatic partition, key, name and type inference. This is then saved to a file.
*Step 2: Make a permanent external table
**`bq mk â€“-external_table_definition=/tmp/common_crawl_tabledef demo_common_crawl.common_crawl_external_live`
*From within BigQuery, you can then query demo_common_crawl.common_crawl_external_live table.

Can also import high partitioned files into big query managed storage

`Bq load â€“-hive_partitioning_mode=AUTO â€“-source_format=PARQUET -â€“autodetect â€“-hive_paritioning_source_uri_prefix=gs://fhc-index/table/cc-main/warc demo_common_crawl.common_crawl_incremental_demo_live gs://fh-commoncrawl/cc-index/table/cc-main/warc/crawl=CC-MAIN-20arch/part-00197-Z48eba37-08f7-4a53-a4b4-d990640e4be4.c000.gz.parquet`

The above command loads a single file into a managed table while also recognizing and loading the partition columns.

Below pulled from Introduction to Google Cloud Platform PDF

BigQuery [img[images/GCP_Icon_BigQuery.png]] : Google Cloudâ€™s petabyte-scale analytics data warehouse. Data in a 
BigQuery table is encrypted using a data encryption key. Then, even those 
data-encryption keys are encrypted with key-encryption keys for additional security. 
This is known as ''envelope encryption''. BigQuery also allows you to provide your own 
encryption keys should you wish.  

Google File System (''GFS''); handle sharding and storing petabytes of data at 
scale. GFS is the foundation for Cloud Storage and also what would become 
BigQuery managed storage.

MapReduce: (Dataproc [img[images/GCP_Icon_DataProc.png]] ) manage large-scale data processing across large clusters of 
commodity servers. MapReduce programs are automatically parallelized and 
executed on a large cluster of commodity machines

Cloud Big Table [img[images/GCP_Icon_Cloud_BigTable.png]]  â€“ Inpiration behind HBase/MongoDB

Dremel (BigQuery [img[images/GCP_Icon_BigQuery.png]] ): Replaced MapReduce. 
Dremel breaks data into small 
chunks called shards and compresses them into a columnar format across distributed 
storage. It then uses a query optimizer to farm out tasks between the many shards of 
data and the Google data centers full of commodity hardware to process the query in 
parallel and deliver the results. The big leap forward was the service auto-manages 
data imbalances and communication between workers and autoscales to meet your 
query demand. Dremel became the query engine behind BigQuery.

Colossus as a next generation distributed data store, Spanner as a planet-scale 
relational database,
flume and millwheel for data pipelines, Pub/Sub for messaging, and TensorFlow for 
machine learning plus the specialized TPU hardware we saw earlier.

DataProc is fully managed
BigQuery and Dataflow are serverless
If the methods of getting data in are similar between Serverless and Fully Managed, you generally want to use Serverless.

*Cloud SQL
**Managed Postgres and MySQL instances
**Scalable for most OLTP workloads
**Benefits from Compute Engine cost optimization (because itâ€™s running on top of Compute Engine)
**Runtime and management configuration
**Data is encrypted in transit and at rest
*Cloud Storage
**Blob storage
**Automatic edge caching
**Different storage classes for different data types
***Standard Storage: Frequently accessed â€œhotâ€ data and/or stored only briefly
***Nearline: Low-cost, highly durable; Plan to read or modify less then once per month
***Coldline: data you plan to read/modify  at most once per quarter
***Archive: used for data archival, online backup or disaster recovery
**Each of the above classes has 3 location options
***Region
***Dual-Region
***Multi-Region
**Object lifecycle management
*Persistent Disk
**Block storage for use with compute VMâ€™s
**Independent from VMs
**Can have up to 16 persistent disks per compute engine VM
**Can attach a single persistent disk to multiple VMs (but as Read Only)
**Highly configurable (HDD or SSDâ€¦, region, zoneâ€¦; resize at any time)
**Managed and optimized infrastructure
*Cloud Filestore
**Managed Network Attached Storage (NAS)
**Shared block storage for compute VMs or containers
**Low latency, low maintenance
**Good for Video processing for example
*Cloud Bigtable
**High performance at scale
**Managed infrastructure
**Library support for multiple languages
**All entity information modeled as a row with a single index (One indexed column = ROWKEY)
**Optimized for sparsely-populated rows; empty cells donâ€™t take up any space
**No transactional guarantees beyond the scope of a single row.
**All information should be kept in a single row
*Cloud Spanner
**Fully managed relational DB (horizontally-scaled, managed RDBMS)
**Distributed transaction support (5 9â€™s availability)
**TrueTime provides a consistent clock to every note in a system
**Built for Googleâ€™s own application
*Cloud Datastore (rebranded to Cloud Firestore)
**Build on App Engine
**Used for managing structured data (like a document database)
**Schemaless
**Limited transaction support
**Performance scales based on size of query results
**Firestore supports offline scenarios
**Firestore shift from an entity to a document model
**Firestore has full transaction support
**3 options for provisioning a new DB
***Cloud Datastore: Standard Cloud Datastore implementation without any Firestore advantages.
***Firestore in Datastore Mode: provisions onto the new storage backend but with Cloud Datastore behavior. This way you still get the strong transactional guarantees from Firestore.
***Cloud Firestore in Native Mode
*Cloud Memorystore
**In-Memory Database; Ideal for caching
**Supports Redis application protocol
**Managed infrastructure

||!Transactional|!Analytical|
|!Source of data|Operational data; OLTPs are the original source of the data|Consolidation data; OLAP data comes from the various OLTP databases|
|!Purpose of data|Control and run fundamental business tasks|Help with planning, problem solving, and decision support|
|!What the data shows|Reveals snapshot of ongoing business processes|Multi-dimensional views of various kinds of business activities|
|!Inserts and updates|Short and fast inserts and updates initiated by end users|Periodic long-running batch jobs refresh the data|
|!Queries|Relativley standardized and simple queries returning relatively few records|Often complex queries involving aggregations|
|!Processing speed|Typically very fast|Depends on amount of data involved; improve query speed with indexes|
|!Space requirements|Can be relatively small if historical data is archived|Larger, more indexes than OLTP|

"""
OLTP - Online Transaction Processing; Transactional systems often 80%/20% write/read
OLAP - Online Analytical Processing; Analytics system have reversed ratio.
"""

Couple of options to store transactional information in Relation Databases

*[img[images/GCP_Icon_Cloud_SQL.png]]Cloud SQL
**Default choice if you have data in Postgres, MySQL or SQL Server
**More cost effective.
**Fully managed relational databases (SQL Server, MySQL, PostgreSQL)
**Accessible by other GCP services. (example, Federated query from Big Query to Cloud SQL)
*[img[images/GCP_Icon_Cloud_Spanner.png]]Cloud Spanner
**Choice if you have a globally distributed database that will be seeing updates from applications in different 
**Could use if your database is too big to fit in a single cloud SQL instance. For many, many GB, you might want to consider using a distributed database.

For Analytical information

*[img[images/GCP_Icon_BigQuery.png]]Big Query
**usually the default for analytical work loads. 
**More cost effective.
**Serverless
*[img[images/GCP_Icon_Cloud_BigTable.png]]Cloud Bigtable 
**better choice if you need huge data amounts for throughputs (millions per second)








https://www.howtogeek.com/762863/how-to-generate-ssh-keys-in-windows-10-and-windows-11/

* In Cmd window, enter `ssh-keygen`
* After you type your command hit Enter, and then youâ€™ll be prompted to give your key a name and save it in a specific location. If you use the defaults then it will save your keys in C:\User[YourUserName].ssh â€”assuming the C drive is where your user account is stored.
* Next, youâ€™ll be asked to enter a passphrase. 
* Thatâ€™s it your keys are created, saved, and ready for use. You will see you have two files in your â€œ.sshâ€ folder: â€œid_rsaâ€ with no file extension and â€œid_rsa.pub.â€ The latter is the key you upload to servers to authenticate while the former is the private key that you donâ€™t share with others.

|`git init`|initialized a new git repository (on your local machine, do this within the directory you want to use with git)|
|`git add <filename>`|used to save a specific filename to your local repository|
|`git add .` |save everything since the last change; this is should probably be used more often instead of specifying a file, like above command.|
|`git commit -m 'describe changes here'`|commit the changes to local repository with a description of what changes were made.|
|`git log`|Look at information from past saves|
|`git checkout <hash value of change from log>`|This will create a different branch|
|`git remote add origin http://github/....` |link local directory to external site (github, gitlab, bitbucket)|
|`git push -u origin master`|Upload (PUSH) files from local repository to github site (or gitlab, bitbucket..); all code is on master branch. origin is the name of remote repository. By default, ''origin ''is the name given to the remote repository you cloned from. ''master'': This is the name of the branch you're pushing.|
|`git checkout -b name_of_new_branch`	|Makes a new branch|
|`git branch`|Visual see master and its branches|
|`git push origin name_of_new_branch`|Moves the changes from your branch up to the git site being used|
|`git pull origin master`|synch up changes that are on github down to your local copy of the repository|

|Pull Request|Request that the change in a branch be merged with the master branch|
|Merge pull request	|If changes are okay, merge the changes in the new branch with the master branch|
|origin|remote repository|

"Rebasing": more advanced topic






If you make changes/additions to a repository on the local machine, navigate to the repository directory via cmd console and enter
`git status`

This will list any changes made since the last sync-up. For this example, I'd added a new directory named images which contained a couple of png files.
To add that new dirctory to github:
git add images/ 

Then:
`git status`

This will list the new items or changes that need to be committed. Something like this:

```
C:\Users\taber\Documents\GitHub\TBwiki>git status
On branch main
Your branch is up to date with 'origin/main'.

Untracked files:
  (use "git add <file>..." to include in what will be committed)
        images/

nothing added to commit but untracked files present (use "git add" to track)
```

To Add any new files/directories, you'll need to use `add`
(or if there are multiple items to add and you just want them all the use `add -A` )


```
C:\Users\taber\Documents\GitHub\TBwiki>git add images/

C:\Users\taber\Documents\GitHub\TBwiki>git status
On branch main
Your branch is up to date with 'origin/main'.

Changes to be committed:
  (use "git restore --staged <file>..." to unstage)
        new file:   images/Putty_SSH_Plex2021_Tunnel_settings.png
        new file:   images/VNC_SSH_Plex2021_Tunnel_settings.png
```


To then commit those changes to your local repository, with a description:

`git commit -m "Description text"`


```
C:\Users\taber\Documents\GitHub\TBwiki>git commit -m "Added 2 images for VNC_SSH setup"
[main be5d75d] Added 2 images for VNC_SSH setup
 2 files changed, 0 insertions(+), 0 deletions(-)
 create mode 100644 images/Putty_SSH_Plex2021_Tunnel_settings.png
```

`git all -A`

The YAML file is used to define the Habu CLI configuration, including the parameters, options, settings and preferences applied to the CLI installation. Parameters include accountName, organizationName, role, warehouse, user and password (optional).

Below is a YAML file example:


```
accountName: ACME_ACCOUNT
organizationName: ACME ORG
role: ACCOUNTADMIN
warehouse: CLEAN_ROOM_SETUP_WH
user: clean_room_user
password: changeme
```


The Habu CLI uses the YAML file information to specify the Snowflake instance and the user with the AccountAdmin role in order to enable the installation command to run and finalize the CLI installation. Habu does not collect and store any information from the YAML file, as it is strictly used for the CLI installation.

The HBASE system uses a Epoch time (with milliseconds) for it's timestamp values.
Because HBASE doesn't store all columns for a person on one row, I selected one standard AMLK bookname to base the return on.

You can search the table based on a date range using:

```
scan 'hb_wcc_cdev_global_enhancement:AMLK_STOR_2', {COLUMNS => 'AILM5BC3:AACD', TIMERANGE => [1615748423000, 1616007623000] }
```


The Epoch time can be determined with the online site below, just make sure to use the 13 digit value to include millisecond information. Noticed I have 000 at the end of all my queries.
https://www.epochconverter.com/

Counts can also be done using:

```
count 'hb_wcc_cdev_global_enhancement:AMLK_STOR_2' , {COLUMNS => 'AILM5BC3:AACD', TIMERANGE => [1615878023000, 1616007623000] }
```

```
get 'hb_wcc_cdev_ovt_enhancement:model_score', 9004470
```

Search for records with a certain values (like a where clause)
``SingleColumnValueFilter('<family>', '<qualifier>', <compare operator>, '<comparator>')``

Example; returns 5 records with only a value of 31 for the FPST book name

```
>scan 'hb_wcc_cdev_global_enhancement:AMLK_STOR_1', {FILTER => "SingleColumnValueFilter('GEOG4674','FPST',=,'binary:31') AND ColumnPrefixFilter ('FPST')", LIMIT => 5}
```



Look for records that were inserted by a certain PQID; return only the INS_PQID row (good for getting counts inserted on a certain run. The returned ROW value is the consmr_id

```
>scan 'hb_wcc_cdev_ovt_enhancement:ENHS_STOR', {COLUMNS => 'amerilink:INS_PQID', FILTER => "SingleColumnValueFilter('amerilink','INS_PQID',=,'binary:26354')"}
```
