"""
HDFS command line
List of directory you're in:
hdfs dfs -ls 

There is no cd command in hdfs, you have to manually call out the path using -ls to get the directories/files in it

List of contents of certain directory:
hdfs dfs -ls /dir/subdir/dir1

Recursive list of contents and sub-directories
hdfs dfs -ls -R

Display contents of document
cat <file-name>
hdfs dfs -cat /dir/subdir/dir1/filename

Search for specific file name mask (below searches for any file starting with DISP
ls -lrt DISP*

Copy file
cp <src> <dest>
hadoop fs -cp /user/dir/subdir/filename /user/dir/subdir/copyname












It might sometimes be needed to run a repair on HDFS/HIVE tables. The syntax for that command is below. You'll need to be logged into Edge server via Putty and enter into hive mode before running it.

```
msck repair table <db_name>.<table_name>
```







! Image Formatting

Images can be included in WikiText with the following syntax:

```
[img[Motovun Jack.jpg]]
[img[https://tiddlywiki.com/favicon.ico]]
```

You can also insert images from the editor toolbar. Click ''picture'' ({{$:/core/images/picture}}) and select a picture file.

If the image source is the title of an image tiddler then that tiddler is directly displayed. Otherwise it is interpreted as a URL and an HTML `<img>` tag is generated with the `src` attribute containing the URL.

A tooltip can also be specified:

```
[img[An explanatory tooltip|Motovun Jack.jpg]]
```

Attributes can be provided to specify CSS classes and the image width and height:

```
[img width=32 [Motovun Jack.jpg]]
[img width=32 class="tc-image" [Motovun Jack.jpg]]
```

Note that attributes can be specified as transclusions or variable references:

```
[img width={{!!mywidth}} class=<<image-classes>> [Motovun Jack.jpg]]
```

The image syntax is a shorthand for invoking the ImageWidget.

! Displaying Images via Transclusion

You can also display an image stored in a tiddler by transcluding that tiddler. The disadvantage of this approach is that there is no direct way to control the size of the image.

```
{{Motovun Jack.jpg}}
```

Renders as:

{{Motovun Jack.jpg}}








"""
To manually run a workflow, open the Informatica PowerCenter Workflow Manager application (orange/yellow). Connect to the repository. Look in the Workflows directory of the client.
 
With now running Tidal, I would run into an issue where Informatica would compain about no Intergration Service. 
I got the following information from Lindsey Snow:
 
For Integration service name â€“ 
These get assigned by Tidal when a job is run via Tidal. So they are usually left blank for Tidal to take care of. 
 
The exception is when we want to run directly from Informatica â€“ then we have to manually assign it. 
The way you tried to start the job in Informatica was correct. 
It just needs to have an integration service assigned. The have named the integration services differently in dev/test/prod â€“ and you can only assign a service that exists in the environment you are running in â€“ so we cant do it for test/prod. 
To assign an integration service â€“ 
Go into workflow manager 
Open the workflow 
Click on Workflows menu at the top of the screen
Select EDIT
On the integration service line, click on browse integration services, then select the value from the list â€“ there will only be one. 
 
OK, then save (Unfortunately I didn't have permissions to do this edit of the workflow)













"""(taken from Jarvis Demo video)
Also see entry for AirFlow
Overview Read me doc:
https://gitlab.com/2sixty/consumer-engagement-platform/yellowstone/jarvis/-/blob/main/README.md


Jarvis uses apache airflow as its backbone to automate and schedule the DAG creation and allow us to plan future and look behind as we just read.
"""
!! Principles

# Provides a centralized library to deal with Google Cloud specific data processing automation
# Provides standardized configuration to define different workflows per feed
# Provide templates for dag execution


!! Implementation
There are two directories under Jarvis.

# base --> Contain the jarvis core library
# Customer --> Contains the DAG definition and configuration for customer specific feeds.


!! Architecture


!! Configuration
The configuration contains 4 major section

# ''DAG Metadata''
## Describes the feed name and the owner of the dag
## Also contains the schedule for the dag to run.

# ''GCP Project''
##Describe GCP project id, region and the dataproc cluster name to be used for this dag execution

# ''Dataproc Cluster Config''
##This cluster is dependent on a static bucket to be specified in the configuration to preserve the system logs and job history
##It contains the Dataproc hardware configuration for Master and Worker nodes
## Also contains the system image to be used which impact the spark version availability fo the dataproc jobs

# ''WCC Job Config''
## Contains the array of job configuration which are to be executed in sequence.
## Each entry in the array has the job specific information.
## These jobs are executed in the order they are defined in the config file.




!! Job Factory
Jarvis supports the following job types

# HTTP Job -
# SPARK Job -
# PYTHON Job -
# DATAPROC Job -
# GCS Sensor Job -
# PGP Job


!! XOperators
Jarvis exposes XOperators for end users which allows them to persist the state of the execution through use of XCOM Pull and Push Variables.
Each XOperator extends the existing Airflow operators and implement the XCOM Variable communication during the processing / execution of the application.

1. XHTTPOperator

# Calls the Airflow HttpOperator while pushing the result of the execution to the configured Xcom variable.
# Can also get the state from configured Xcom pull variable and pass as argument to the Http Call.


2. XBashOperator

# Calls the Airflow Bash operator while pulling the xcom variable and appending its value to the end of the argument list as additional parameter.
# Pushes the result to Configured XCOM variable.


3. XPythonOperator

# Call the Airflow Python Operator and passes the user configured function.
# Only support the functions implemented by WCC Engineering.
# XCom variables can be pushed and pulled and the result of the above function can be added to Xcom variables.


4. XDataprocCreateOperator and XDataprocDeleteOperator

# Call the Airflow Dataproc Operator and pass the user configured values.
# XDataprocCreateOperator pushes the xcom variable to indicate the cluster creation status. (True or False)
# XDataprocDeleteOperator uses the same variable to check the status and perform cluster delete operation if status is True.


5. XGCSObjectPrefixSensorOperator

# Call the Airflow GCSObjectPrefixSensor Operator and pass the user configured values.
# The operator would be used to monitor specific bucket location for any change during the given time interval (DELTA).
# The operator execution depends on the POKE interval configurable as additional parameter in job json.
# A list of comma separate file names would be returned as part of the associated XCOM variable.
# The consumer of the operator (Downstream jobs) has to parse the list and perform the business logic.


!! Usage

# To define a new DAG we have to create a configuration by referring to any of the existing config and the copy the template python file and modify it to refer this configuration
# Put this config file in Airflow variables.
# Put this python file in DAG bucket.
# Airflow will load the dag in some duration and schedule it per configuration


!! New Jobs using existing XOperators

1.PGP JOb using XPythonOperator and XBashOperator

```
		1. It supports the encryption and decryption of the files using the Private and public key respectively.
		2. Keys needs to be stored in google secret pass the secret name as key ring in the Job Config.
		3. For encryption(Private key), PassPhrase also needs to be saved in the google secret.
		4. This job include three steps 
			a. PGP Preprocess (using XPythonOperator)
			b. PGP encyption/decryption (using XBashOperator)
			c. PGP Postprocess (using XPythonOperator)
		5. Preprocess copies the file to the local directory for the airflow composer cluster to encrypt or decrypt.
		6. PGP decryption/encryption does the decryption/encryption of the file using the keys.
		7. Postprocess moves the encrypted/decrypted file back to the client folder for further processing.
```

!!Multiple file processing Support by jarvis

Jarvis extends to support the multiple file processing for same feed under the single client. For example if we receive multiple file at simultaneously for same feed under the same client. It start processing in FIFS(first come first serve) to maintain the client data integrity.
For performing that it has two steps Preprocess and Post processing.



1.''Preprocess(using XPythonOperator):''

```
			1. It check the last processing file and in the processing folder
			2. Then it checks the last updated file with the given prefix in the client input folder and moves the file to the processing folder.
```


2.''Postprocess(using XPythonOperator):''

```
			1. It moves the file from processing folder to archive folder once all the processing is completed.
```

!!Sample Config files for each Job:

1. ''HTTP job:''

```
		For hitting below URL 
			URL: http://10.117.49.197:8090/platform-services/generate-metadata/v1/common/qtc/NCOA-EXTRACT
				a. Client code and file pattern are interchangeable as per the use case 
				b. connection_id: Aiflow connection variable needs to be created. With the details.
							connection name:  cep_qa_qtc_common_MetaService
							Connection(type): HTTP 
							host : http://10.117.49.197
							port : 8090			
				
				{
					"Sequence": 0,
					"job_name": "get_metadata_json",
					"type": "HTTP",
					"wcc_job": {
						"xcom_push_variable": "wcc_ingestion_metadata_json",
						"xcom_pull_variable": "False",
						"input_params": {
							"client_code": "qtc",
							"file_pattern": "NCOA-EXTRACT"
						},
					"connection_id": "cep_qa_qtc_common_MetaService",
					"endpoint": "/platform-services/generate-metadata/v1/common/"
					}
				}
```


2. ''Preprocess job :''

```
		function_name: Name of the functiin the Util file.
		Op_kwargs: kwargs(keyword arguments) for the function.
		client_input_bucket: GCS Bucket where client files will arrive.
		processing_bucket: GCS bucket in which file processing will take place.
		environment: gcpqa/gcpdev/gcpuat/gcpprod
		filepattern_startswith: file prefix
		client: client name	
		{
			"Sequence": 0,
			"job_name": "PreProcess_Job",
			"type": "PYTHON",
			"wcc_job": {
				"xcom_push_variable": "processing_file",
				"xcom_pull_variable": "updated_files_list",
				"function_config": {
					"function_name": "pre_process_job",
					"op_kwargs": {
						"client_input_bucket": "yellowstone-eng-bucket",
						"processing_bucket": "yellowstone-eng-bucket",
						"environment": "gcpqa",
						"client": "qtc",
						"filepattern_startswith": "ref_sql_test"
					}
				}
			}
		}
```


3. ''PGP job''

```
		airflow_gcs_bucket: Airflow Composer cluster GCS bucket.
		archive_bucket: Bucket where file will be moved after the processing			
		{
			"Sequence": 0,
			"job_name": "pre_process_pgp_decryption",
			"type": "PYTHON",
			"wcc_job": {
				"xcom_push_variable": "False",
				"xcom_pull_variable": "False",
				"function_config": {
				"function_name": "pgp_pre_processor",
				"op_kwargs": {
					"client_input_bucket": "yellowstone-eng-bucket",
					"environment": "gcpqa",
					"client": "qtc",
					"airflow_gcs_bucket": "us-east1-ys-composer-trust--fde7e4ad-bucket",
					"key_ring": "test_sample_pgp_pub",
					"project_id": "yellowstone-dev-317112",
					"filepattern_startswith": "ref_sql_test"
				}
				}
			}
		},
		{
			"Sequence": 1,
			"job_name": "pgp_file_decryption",
			"type": "PGP",
			"wcc_job": {
				"process": "decryption",
				"xcom_push_variable": "False",
				"xcom_pull_variable": "False",
				"client": "qtc",
				"key_ring": "test_sample_pgp_pub",
				"airflow_gcs_bucket": "us-east1-ys-composer-trust--fde7e4ad-bucket",
				"filepattern_startswith": "ref_sql_test"
			}
		},
		{
			"Sequence": 2,
			"job_name": "post_process_file_decryption",
			"type": "PYTHON",
			"wcc_job": {
				"xcom_push_variable": "False",
				"xcom_pull_variable": "False",
				"function_config": {
				"function_name": "pgp_post_processor",
				"op_kwargs": {
					"process": "decryption",
					"client_input_bucket": "yellowstone-eng-bucket",
					"archive_bucket": "yellowstone-eng-bucket",
					"client": "qtc",
					"environment": "gcpqa",
					"airflow_gcs_bucket": "us-east1-ys-composer-trust--fde7e4ad-bucket",
					"filepattern_startswith": "ref_sql_test"
				}
				}
			}
		}
```


4. ''Postprocess Job:''

```
		{
			"Sequence": 0,
			"job_name": "PostProcess_Job",
			"type": "PYTHON",
			"wcc_job": {
				"xcom_push_variable": "False",
				"xcom_pull_variable": "False",
				"function_config": {
				"function_name": "post_process_job",

To split a string apart, based on a delimiter:


```
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Example string
        String input = "Car, Dog, Tree, Orange";
        
        // Split the string by commas
        String[] parts = input.split(",\\s*"); // Split by comma and optional space

        // Check if there are enough parts
        if (parts.length >= 3) {
            // Get the value in the 3rd position (index 2)
            String thirdValue = parts[2];
            System.out.println("The value in the 3rd position is: " + thirdValue);
        } else {
            System.out.println("The input string does not have enough values.");
        }
    }
}
```

				.basic(tokenUser, tokenPass)
				.formParam("grant_type", "client_credentials");

				.accept(ContentType.JSON).header("Authorization", "Bearer " + token).queryParam("name", params.get(0))
				.queryParam("description", params.get(1)).queryParam("startAt", params.get(2))
				.queryParam("endAt", params.get(3)).queryParam("type", params.get(4))
				.queryParam("parameters[ENABLE_VIEW_QUERY]", params.get(5))
				.queryParam("parameters[CROWD_SIZE]", params.get(6))
				.queryParam("parameters[DATA_DECIBEL]", params.get(7))
				.queryParam("parameters[ENABLE_EXPORT", params.get(8));

				"Bearer " + token);

"""
https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/array-vs-arraylist-in-java/

An array is basic functionality provided by Java. ArrayList is part of collection framework in Java. Therefore array members are accessed using [], while ArrayList has a set of methods to access elements and modify them.

Array is a fixed size while ArrayList is not.
If an ArrayList needs to be expanded, it actually creates a new array 1.5x the size of the original one and copies all of the original values that were in the original ArrayList to a new ArrayList.
ArrayList is also inefficient when needing to add/remove elements in the middle or beginning of the array. If there are 1000 elements in an ArrayList and you need to delete the 3rd element, it would have to shift each element past the 3rd over one, so that's 997 moves that would need to be made.


Array can contain both primitive data types and objects of a class, depending on array definition.

ArrayList only supports object entries (for example when doing arrayList.add(1) it converts the primitive int to an integer object. But if your array list is to contain primatives, you can just use its wrapper class. So int would use Integer, boolean would use Boolean, long would use Long...

Array example (uses square brackets):
"""

```
//String[] friendsArray = new String[4];
String[] friendsArray2 = {"John", "Chris", "Eric", "Luke"};

//This should print out Chris.
System.out.println(friendsArray[1]);
```

Array List Example (uses greater/less):

```
//ArrayList<String> friendsArrayList = new ArrayList<>();
ArrayList<String> friendsArrayList 2 = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("John", "Chris", "Eric", "Luke"));

//This should print out Chris

//If a primative, like int, you can just use its wrapper class, Integer.
ArrayList<Integer> intArrayList = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4));
```




```
// A Java program to demonstrate differences between array
// and ArrayList
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Arrays;
class Test
{
	public static void main(String args[])
	{
		/* ........... Normal Array............. */
		// Need to specify the size for array
		int[] arr = new int[3];
		arr[0] = 1;
		arr[1] = 2;
		arr[2] = 3;
		// We cannot add more elements to array arr[]

		/*............ArrayList..............*/
		// Need not to specify size
		ArrayList<Integer> arrL = new ArrayList<Integer>();
		arrL.add(1);
		arrL.add(2);
		arrL.add(3);
		arrL.add(4);
		// We can add more elements to arrL

		System.out.println(arrL);
		System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr));
	}
}

```


```
Output:

[1, 2, 3, 4]
[1, 2, 3]
```








"""An array list stores elements within it in consecutive memory addresses.
If you need to add an element to an ArrayList, it will actually create a new ArrayList that is 1.5x the size of the current one and then copy all the elements from the original ArrayList to the new ArrayList and append the new elements

ArrayList is also inefficient when needing to add/remove elements in the middle or beginning of the array because it's structure references elements in relation to the ones directly before and after. 
Example, ff there are 1000 elements in an ArrayList and you need to delete the 3rd element, it would empty out the value in the 3rd memory position and then have to shift each element past the 3rd over one memory address, so that's 997 moves that would need to be made.

However, the ArrayList is much more efficient than a LinkedList when just trying to reference existing elements. There is just a difference if needing to add/remove elements inside the array and if the array is very large.

	public BasePageObject() {
		this.driver = DriverUtilities.getDriver();

		actions = new Actions(driver);
		js=(JavascriptExecutor) driver;
		PageFactory.initElements(driver, this);

	// waits for amount of time specified
	public void sleep(int milliSec) {
		if(milliSec !=0) {
			try {Thread.sleep(milliSec);}
			catch (InterruptedException e) {
				System.out.println(e);
			}
		}
	}
	
	// scrolls down the webpage all the way to the bottom
	public void scroll() {
		try {
			js.executeScript("window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight)");
		}catch (ClassCastException e) {
			Assert.fail("scroll.Execption.ClassCastException"+e.getMessage());
		}catch (WebDriverException e) {
			Assert.fail("scroll.Exception.WebDriverException" + e.getMessage());
		}catch (Exception e) {
			Assert.fail("scroll.Exception.Exception" + e.getMessage());
		}
	}
	
	// scrolls down the webpage by visibility of the element. This method will scroll until the mentioned element is visible on the current page
	// using JSE   @param = element
	
	public void scroll(WebElement element) {
		try {
			js.executeScript("arguments[0].scrollIntoView();", element);
		}catch (ClassCastException e) {
			Assert.fail("scroll.Execption.ClassCastException"+e.getMessage());
		}catch (WebDriverException e) {
			Assert.fail("scroll.Exception.WebDriverException" + e.getMessage());
		}catch (Exception e) {
			Assert.fail("scroll.Exception.Exception" + e.getMessage());
		}
	}
	
	// scrolls down the webpage by hitting the down arrow key
	
	public void scrollDownByHittingPageDownKey(int timesToHit) {
		try {
			robot=new Robot();
			for (int i = 0; i< timesToHit; i++) {
				robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_PAGE_DOWN);
				robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_PAGE_DOWN);
			}
		} catch (AWTException e) {
			System.out.println(e.getMessage());
		}catch (Exception e) {
			System.out.println(e.getMessage());
		}
	}

	// waits for element to be clickable before clicking
	protected void waitToClick(WebElement button) {
		String btnString = formatWord(button);
		System.out.println("Attempting to click on" + btnString + ".....");
		try {
			wait.until(ExpectedConditions.elementToBeClickable(button));
			button.click();
			System.out.println("Button has been successfully clicked.......");
		}catch(StaleElementReferenceException e) {
			System.out.println("Element is stale...Refreshing....");
			try {
				button=refreshElement(button);
				button.click();
				System.out.println("Button has been successfully clicked.......");
			}catch(Exception e2) {
				System.out.println("Element still not clickable");
				Assert.fail("waitToClick exception for " + btnString);
			}
		}
	}
	
	//waits to click using JSE

		protected void waitToClickUsingJSE(WebElement button) {
			String btnString = formatWord(button);

			try {
				wait.until(ExpectedConditions.elementToBeClickable(button));
				js.executeScript("arguments[0].click();", button);

		}
		
		//waits for element to be clickable before hovering over it
		protected void waitToHoverOver(WebElement element) {
			String btnString = formatWord(element);
			System.out.println("Attempting to hover over  " + btnString);
			try {
				wait.until(ExpectedConditions.elementToBeClickable(element));
				actions.moveToElement(element).build().perform();
			}catch(StaleElementReferenceException e){
				System.out.println("Element is stale...Refreshing....");
				try {
					element=refreshElement(element);
					actions.moveToElement(element).build().perform();
					System.out.println("Button has been successfully clicked.......");
				}catch(Exception e2) {
					System.out.println("Element still not clickable");
					Assert.fail("waitToClick exception for " + btnString);
				}
			}
			
		}
		
		//waits for visibility of element
		public void waitForVisibility(WebElement element, int timeout) {
			System.out.println("Waiting for visibility of element......");
			try {
				wait= new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(timeout));
			}catch(TimeoutException e) {
				Assert.fail("WaitForVisibility.Exception.TimeoutException" + e.getMessage());
			}catch(NoSuchElementException e) {
				Assert.fail("NoSuchElementException" + e.getMessage());
			}catch(WebDriverException e) {
				Assert.fail("WebDriverException" + e.getMessage());
			}finally {
				wait= new WebDriverWait(driver,Default_Timeout);
			}
		}
		
		private String formatWord(WebElement element) {
			String locatorKey= getElementID(element);
			String splitFieldName= getPrettyText(locatorKey);
			if(splitFieldName==null|| StringUtils.isEmpty(locatorKey)) {
				return locatorKey;
			}
			return splitFieldName;
		}
		
		// selects an option by visible text from drop down list using Select Class
		public void selectFromDropdown(WebElement dropdown, String text) {
			String ddString= formatWord(dropdown);
			try {
				wait.until(ExpectedConditions.elementToBeClickable(dropdown));
				Select list = new Select(dropdown);

			}catch(StaleElementReferenceException e) {
				try {
					dropdown= refreshElement(dropdown);
					Select list = new Select(dropdown);
					list.selectByVisibleText(text);
				}catch(Exception e2) {
					Assert.fail("StaleElementException..." + e.getMessage());
				}
			}catch(TimeoutException e) {
				Assert.fail("TimeoutException");
			}catch(NoSuchElementException e) {
				Assert.fail("NoSuchElementException");
			}catch (WebDriverException e) {
				Assert.fail("WebDriverException");
			}catch(Exception e) {
				Assert.fail("Exception" + e.getMessage());
			}
		}
		
		public void switchToIFrameByNameOrId(String nameOrId) {

		public String getElementID(WebElement element) {
			String strElement= "Element: " + element.toString();
			try {
				String[] localData= null;
				if(element.toString().contains("->")) {
					localData = element.toString().split("-> ")[1].split(": ");
					localData[1]= localData[1].substring(0,localData[1].length()-1);
				}else if (element.toString().contains("By.partialLinkText")) {
					localData= getRegEx("(.)By.cssSelector: (.*)\\1", element.toString());
				}else if (element.toString().contains("By.cssSelector")) {
					String regEx= "(.)By.cssSelector: (.*)\\1";
					Pattern p= Pattern.compile(regEx);
					Matcher m= p.matcher(element.toString());
					String cssSelector="";
					if(m.find())cssSelector=m.group(m.groupCount());
					cssSelector=cssSelector.substring(cssSelector.lastIndexOf('_')+1);
					localData= new String[]{"", cssSelector};
				}else if(element.toString().contains("By.id")) {
					String[] idParts= element.toString().split(":");
					String idName= idParts[1].substring(idParts[1].lastIndexOf('_')+1);
					localData= new String[] {"", idName};
				}else if(element.toString().contains("By.linkText")) {
					localData= getRegEx("(.)By.linkText: (.*)\\1", element.toString());
				}else {
					localData= new String[] {"", element.toString()};
				}
				return (localData != null ? localData[1] : null);
			} catch (NullPointerException npe) {
				Assert.fail();
			}catch(ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException e) {
				Assert.fail();
			}catch(Exception e) {
				Assert.fail();
			}
			return "";
			
		}
		
		public String[] getRegEx(String regEx, String strInput) {
			Pattern p = Pattern.compile(regEx);
			Matcher m = p.matcher(strInput);
			if(m.find()) return new String[] {"", m.group(m.groupCount())};
			return new String[] {"",""};
		}
		
		public String getPrettyText(String locatorKey) {
			String locator = getRegularPrettyText(locatorKey);
			if(locator==null) locator= getAEMPrettyText(locatorKey);
			return locator;
		}
		
		public String getRegularPrettyText(String locatorKey) {
			String locator="";
			try {
				Class<?> cls= Class.forName(this.getClass().getCanonicalName());
				Field[] fields= cls.getDeclaredFields();
				for(Field field : fields) {
					Annotation[] ano = field.getDeclaredAnnotations();
					for(Annotation a : ano) {
						String[] str= a.toString().split(",");
						String newStr="";
						for(String how: str) {
							if(how.contains("using=")) {
								newStr = how;
							}
						}
						int locatorStartIndex = newStr.indexOf('=')+1;
						locator= newStr.substring(locatorStartIndex);
						if(locator.equals(locatorKey)) {
							return field.getName().replaceAll("(.)([A-Z])","$1 $2");
						}
					}
				}
			}catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {
				System.out.println(e.getMessage());
			}
			return null;
		}
		
		public String getAEMPrettyText(String locatorKey) {
			String locator = "";
			try {
				Class<?> cls=this.getClass().getSuperclass();
				Field[] fil = cls.getDeclaredFields();
				for(Field f : fil) {
					Annotation[] annotation3 = f.getDeclaredAnnotations();
					for(Annotation ano : annotation3) {
						String[] str = ano.toString().split(",");
						String newStr="";
						for(String how : str) {
							if(how.contains("using=")) {
								newStr=how;
								break;
							}
						}
						locator = newStr.substring(newStr.indexOf('=')+1);
						if(locator.equals(locatorKey)) {
							return f.getName().replaceAll("(.)([A-Z])","$1 $2");
						}
					}
				}
			}catch (Exception e) {
				System.out.println(e.getMessage());
			}
			return getElementString(locatorKey);
		}
		
		public String getElementString(String locatorKey) {
			if(isXpath(locatorKey)) {
				try {
					WebElement element= driver.findElement(By.xpath(locatorKey));
					return element.getText();
				}catch(Exception e) {
					return locatorKey;
				}
			}
			return null;
		}
		
		public boolean isXpath(String xPath) {
			try {
				XPathFactory factory = XPathFactory.newInstance();
				XPath xpath = factory.newXPath();
				xpath.compile(xPath);
				return true;
			}catch (Exception e) {
				return false;
			}
		}
		
		public WebElement refreshElement(WebElement element) {
			Map<String, String> map= parseElementLocator(element);
			return getElement(map.get(TYPE), map.get(LOCATOR));
		}
		
		public WebElement getElement(String locatorType, String locatorValue) {
			By by = getElementBy(locatorType, locatorValue);
			return driver.findElement(by);
		}
		
		public By getElementBy(String locatorType, String locatorValue) {
			By by = null;
			switch(locatorType.toLowerCase()) {
			case "classname":
			case "class name":
				by= By.className(locatorValue);
				break;
			case "css":
			case "cssselector":
			case "selector":
				by=By.cssSelector(locatorValue);
				break;
			case "id":
				by=By.id(locatorValue);
				break;
			case "linktext":
			case "link text" :
				by=By.linkText(locatorValue);
				break;
			case "name":
				by=By.name(locatorValue);
				break;
			case "partiallinktext":
			case "partial link text":
				by=By.partialLinkText(locatorValue);
				break;
			case "tagname":
			case "tag name":
				by=By.tagName(locatorValue);
				break;
			case "xpath":
				by=By.xpath(locatorValue);
				break;
			default: 
				System.out.println("Unknown Element Type....");
			}
			return by;
		}
		
		private Map<String,String> parseElementLocator(WebElement element){
			Map <String,String> map = new HashMap<>();
			String elementString= element.toString();
			String sElement = "";
			if(elementString.contains("-> ")) {
				sElement= elementString.split("-> ")[1];
			}else if (elementString.contains("DefaultElementLocator")) {
				sElement= elementString.split("DefaultElementLocator '")[1];
			}
			String locatorType= sElement.split(": ")[0];
			if(locatorType.startsWith("By")) locatorType = locatorType.substring("By.".length());
			String loc0= sElement.split(": ")[1];
			String theLocator= loc0.substring(0,loc0.length()-1);
			map.put(TYPE, locatorType);
			map.put(LOCATOR, theLocator);
			return map;
		}
		
		public void executeAssertEquals(String description, Object expected, Object actual) {
			boolean comparison = actual.toString().equals(expected.toString())? true:false;
			String status= comparison ? "PASSED" : "FAILED";
			String baseMessage= description + " | STATUS: " + status;
			String appendMessage = "Expected: \"" + expected + "\" |ACTUAL: \"" + actual + "\"";
			System.out.println(baseMessage);
			System.out.println(appendMessage);
			Assert.assertTrue(comparison);
			
			listOfScreenshots.add(captureScreenshotForReport());
			listOfScreenshotDescriptions.add(baseMessage + ", " + appendMessage);
			
		}
		
		public void executeAssertTrue(String description, boolean condition) {
			String status = condition ? "PASSED" : "FAILED";
			String baseMessage = description + " | STATUS: " + status;
			String appendMessage = "Expected: \"" + "TRUE"+ "\" | Actual: \"" + String.valueOf(condition).toUpperCase()+"\"";
			System.out.println(baseMessage);
			System.out.println(appendMessage);
			Assert.assertTrue(condition);
			
			listOfScreenshots.add(captureScreenshotForReport());
			listOfScreenshotDescriptions.add(baseMessage + ", " + appendMessage);
			
		}
		
		public void executeAssertIsElementDisplayed(String description, String locatorType, String locatorValue) {
			boolean condition = false;
			try {
				condition = getElement(locatorType, locatorValue).isDisplayed();
				System.out.println(locatorValue + condition);
			}catch(NoSuchElementException nsee) {
				System.out.println("NoSuchElementException" +nsee.getMessage());
			}
			String status = condition ? "PASSED" : "FAILED";
			String baseMessage = description + " | STATUS: " + status;
			String appendMessage = "Expected: \"" + "TRUE"+ "\" | Actual: \"" + String.valueOf(condition).toUpperCase()+"\"";
			System.out.println(baseMessage);
			System.out.println(appendMessage);
			Assert.assertTrue(condition);
			
			listOfScreenshots.add(captureScreenshotForReport());
			listOfScreenshotDescriptions.add(baseMessage + ", " + appendMessage);
		}
		
		//Captures screenshot image in .png format
		public String captureScreenshot() {
			DateFormat df = new SimpleDateFormat("ddMMyyHHmmss");
			Date dateObj= new Date();
			TakesScreenshot scrShot = ((TakesScreenshot)driver);
			File SrcFile= scrShot.getScreenshotAs(OutputType.FILE);
			String DestFilePath= rootPath + SCRSHOT + df.format(dateObj)+ ".png";
			File DestFile= new File(DestFilePath);
			try {
				FileUtils.copyFile(SrcFile, DestFile);
			}catch(IOException e) {
				e.printStackTrace();
			}
			sleep(5000);
			return DestFilePath;
		}
		
		public byte[] captureScreenshotForReport() {
			final byte[] screenshot=
					((TakesScreenshot)DriverUtilities.getDriver())
					.getScreenshotAs(OutputType.BYTES);
			return screenshot;
		}

		
		public void zoomOut(int timesToHit) {
			try {
	            Robot robot = new Robot();
	            for (int i = 0; i < timesToHit; i++) {

	                robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL);
	                robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_MINUS);
	                robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_MINUS);
	                robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL);
	                Thread.sleep(200);
	            }
	        } catch (Exception e) {
	            e.printStackTrace();
	        }
		}
}

!! Using BufferedReader: 

This method reads text from a character-input stream. It does buffering for efficient reading of characters, arrays, and lines.
The buffer size may be specified, or the default size may be used. The default is large enough for most purposes.

In general, each read request made of a Reader causes a corresponding read request to be made of the underlying character or byte stream. It is therefore advisable to wrap a BufferedReader around any Reader whose read() operations may be costly, such as FileReaders and InputStreamReaders. For example,


```
BufferedReader in = new BufferedReader(Reader in, int size);
```





```
// Java Program to illustrate reading from FileReader
// using BufferedReader
import java.io.*;
public class ReadFromFile2
{
  public static void main(String[] args)throws Exception
  {
  // We need to provide file path as the parameter:
  // double backquote is to avoid compiler interpret words
  // like \test as \t (ie. as a escape sequence)
  File file = new File("C:\\Users\\pankaj\\Desktop\\test.txt");
  
  BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));
  
  String st;
  while ((st = br.readLine()) != null)
    System.out.println(st);
  }
}

Keep catch blocks simple





```
package com.timbuchalka;

import java.util.InputMismatchException;
import java.util.NoSuchElementException;
import java.util.Scanner;

/**
 * Created by timbuchalka on 1/04/2016.
 */
public class Example {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int result = divide();
        System.out.println(result);
    }

    private static int divide() {
        int x, y;
        try {
            x = getInt();
            y = getInt();
        } catch(NoSuchElementException e) {
            throw new ArithmeticException("no suitable input");
        }
        System.out.println("x is " + x + ", y is " + y);
        try {
            return x / y;
        } catch(ArithmeticException e) {
            throw new ArithmeticException("attempt to divide by zero");
        }
    }

    private static int getInt() {
        Scanner s = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println("Please enter an integer ");
        while(true) {
            try {
                return s.nextInt();
            } catch(InputMismatchException e) {
                // go round again.  Read past the end of line in the input first
                s.nextLine();
                System.out.println("Please enter a number using only the digits 0 to 9 ");
            }
        }
    }
}
```

```
    public static void main(String[] args) {

            int primeCount = 0;

        for(int i=10; i <= 50; i++) {

                if(isPrime(i)) {
                    primeCount++;
                    System.out.println(i + " is a Prime number.");
                 //   System.out.println("Prime Count = " + primeCount);

                        if (primeCount == 3) {
                            System.out.println("Exiting loop");
                            break;
                        }
                }
        }

    public static boolean isPrime(int n) {

        if(n == 1) {
            return false;
        }

        for(int i = 2; i<= n/2; i++)
        if(n % i == 0) {
            return false;
        }
        return true;
        }

Very similar to [[While|Java - While loop]], but always do at least one cycle through the do statement before the criteria is checked.

If you want to execute the loop at least once, the `do-while` loop is appropriate.


```
int i = 1;

Original version of Switch, uses across all versions of JDK.


```
// Old version
	switch (value) {
	case 1:
		System.out.println("Value was 1");
		break;
	case 2:
		System.out.println("Value was 2");
		break;
	case 3: case 4: case 5:
		System.out.println("Was a 3, 4 or 5");
		System.out.println("Actually it was a " + value);
		break;
	default:
		System.out.println("Value was not between 1 and 5");
	}
```

Enhanced Switch used by most recent releases of JDK.

```
//Enhanced Switch
	switch (value) {
	case 1 -> System.out.println("Value was 1");
	case 2 -> System.out.println("Value was 2");
	case 3, 4, 5 -> {
		System.out.println("Was a 3, 4 or 5");
		System.out.println("Actually it was a " + value);
	}
	default -> System.out.println("Value was not between 1 and 5");
	}
```







If using the Enhanced Switch method and needing to return information, you'd place the `return `in front of the `switch `statement. Also, if the return needs to include some additional coding within a block, user the `yield `command instead of return for that code block.


```
	public static String getQuarter(String month) {
		
		// Note when returning as part of a call, you put the word return before the switch statement.
		return switch (month) {
		case "JANUARY", "FEBRUARY", "MARCH" -> "1st";
		case "APRIL", "MAY", "JUNE" -> "2nd";
		case "JULY", "AUGUST", "SEPTEMBER" -> "3rd";
		case "OCTOBER", "NOVEMBER", "DECEMBER" -> "4th";
		default -> {
			String badResponse = month + " is bad";
			yield badResponse;	
			// Need to use yield because the code after "->" is a block instead of just a string.
		}
		};
	}
```

Most efficient of the loops is the for loop. If you know the number of iterations in advance, the for loop is often the most suitable.



```
/// Example 1: Print 1...10

for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
	System.out.println(i);
}

/// Example 2: Print Even numbers

for (int i = 2; i <= 10; i += 2) {
	System.out.println(i);
}

/// Example 3: Print Even numbers

for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
	if (i % 2 == 0) {
		System.out.println(i);
	}
}

You can cycle through the array list this way as well.

		int sizeOfArrayList = enteredArrayList.size();

"""
Inheritance is when you sent up a basic class that contains elements that could be common to other more specialized classes but you don't want to have to put those methods manually in each of those specialized classes

For example: if you need to create a specific class for different types of mice, you could create a common mouse class that contains methods for left, right click and scroll wheel actions. Then reference that common mouse class in more specialized classes.

Example would be classes Mouse.java, MouseExtreme.java, MousePlus.java, MouseXL.java
Mouse.java would contain leftClick, rightClick, scrollUp and scrollDown methods.

For the specialized mouse classes, they would reference the common Mouse class using `extends`:

''public class'' MouseExtreme ''extends ''Mouse { 
...}
"""

[[Got this example from Alex Lee Youtube|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zbVAU7lK25Q]]

Example of class inheritance. Fish inherits attributes from Animal class.


```
class Animal:
    def __init__(self):
        self.num_eyes = 2

    def breathe(self):
        print("Inhale, exhale.")

class Fish(Animal):
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()

    def breathe(self):
        super().breathe()
        print("doing this underwater.")

    def swim(self):
        print("moving in water.")

nemo = Fish()
nemo.breathe()
```








https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se17/html/jls-3.html#jls-3.9






Linked List could be considered an alternative to an ArrayList.

A linked list does not store elements in consecutive memory addresses like an ArrayList. Each element is stored in a separate memory address, not necessarily together. The elements are still structured in such a way where their location is in relation to the elements directly before and after them. However, if an element needs to be added/removed in the middle of the array then it doesn't need to shift any of the existing element's address position. It just updates the memory address references to the elements directly in front of and behind where the element was added/removed. 

However, the ArrayList is much more efficient than a LinkedList when just trying to reference existing elements. There is just a difference if needing to add/remove elements inside the array.
But the smaller the array, the less difference in efficiency is seen.

''A Linked List will generally be better for very large arrays where you know there will be the need to add/remove elements (especially further towards the front of the array)''

<dependencies>
    <!-- Logging -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.apache.logging.log4j</groupId>
        <artifactId>log4j-api</artifactId>
        <version>2.14.1</version>
    </dependency>

    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.apache.logging.log4j</groupId>
        <artifactId>log4j-core</artifactId>
        <version>2.14.1</version>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>

```

!Create Log4j2.xml Config file
Create a file named log4j2.xml in the src/main/resources directory. 

This should include the function name and line number information with each log output line as well as make them click-able in the Eclipse Console output.

```
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<Configuration status="WARN">
    <Appenders>
        <Console name="Console" target="SYSTEM_OUT">
            <PatternLayout pattern="%d{yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss} [%t] %-5level %C.%M(%F:%L) - %msg%n"/>
        </Console>
        <File name="File" fileName="logs/app.log">
            <PatternLayout pattern="%d{yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss} [%t] %-5level %C.%M(%F:%L) - %msg%n"/>
        </File>
    </Appenders>
    <Loggers>
        <Root level="info">
            <AppenderRef ref="Console"/>
            <AppenderRef ref="File"/>
        </Root>
    </Loggers>
</Configuration>
```

import org.apache.logging.log4j.LogManager;
import org.apache.logging.log4j.Logger;

public class MyClassName {

     private static final Logger logger = LogManager.getLogger(MyClassName.class);

     public static void main(String[] args) {
        if (args.length != 2) {
            logger.info("Usage: java CsvFieldLengthAnalyzer <csv-file-path> <field-name>");
            return;
        }

        String csvFilePath = args[0];
        String fieldName = args[1];

        try {
            analyzeFieldLengths(csvFilePath, fieldName);
        } catch (IOException | CsvValidationException e) {
            logger.error("Exception occurred", e);
        }
    }
}

"""
Map is a set of key/value pairs. similar to Python Dictionary.


Example (keeping track of Employee names and IDs):
Note that the types below (`<String,Integer>`) must be Java Classes, not primitives
"""

```
HashMap<String,Integer> empIds = new HashMap<>();

empIds.put("John", 12345);
empIds.put("Carl", 54321);
empIds.put("Jerry", 888);

System.out.println(empIds);

```

Output (notice a different order); maps don't guarantee return in a certain order, they just keep track of the key/value pairs

`{Carl=54321, John=12345, Jerry=888}`

"""To get the value for a specific record, use `.get`. 
The below would return `54321`
"""

```
System.out.println(empIds.get("Carl"));
```
"""To see if a key exists, use `.containsKey`. 
The below would return `true`
"""

```
System.out.println(empIds.containsKey("Jerry"));
```
"""To see if a value exists, use `.containsKey`. 
The below would return `true` for the first and `false` for the second
"""

```
System.out.println(empIds.containsValue(888));
System.out.println(empIds.containsValue(123));
```
"""To replace a value in a Map, there are two way.
One is to use `.replace`, which will only update a value if the key exists.
The other is to use `.put`, which will update an existing value but additionally, if the key doesn't already exist it will create it too.
"""

```
empIds.put("John", 98765); //Updates John
empIds.replace("John", 98765); //Updates John
empIds.replace("Kramar", 4545); //Does nothing since Kramar doesn't exist already
```
"""An variation to put and `.replace` is `.putIfAbsent`.
In this case, it will only insert a key/value if it doesn't already exist.
So the first line will insert a key/value for Steve but the second won't do anything to the existing John entry
"""

```
empIds.putIfAbsent("Steve", 222); //inserts Steve
empIds.putIfAbsent("John", 666); //Does nothing since John already existed
```
"""To remove a key/value pair is to use .remove
"""

```
empIds.remove("Steve"); //will remove the Steve key/value pair
```






Java naming conventions help ensure that code is readable, maintainable, and consistent. Here are the general naming conventions:

! Classes
* **Convention**: PascalCase (also known as UpperCamelCase)
* **Example**: `Customer`, `AccountService`, `EmployeeDetails`

! Interfaces
* **Convention**: PascalCase
* **Example**: `Runnable`, `Comparable`, `List`

! Methods
* **Convention**: camelCase
* **Example**: `getCustomerName()`, `calculateTotal()`, `printDetails()`

! Variables
* **Convention**: camelCase
* **Example**: `customerName`, `totalAmount`, `employeeDetails`

! Constants
* **Convention**: UPPER_CASE_WITH_UNDERSCORES
* **Example**: `MAX_VALUE`, `DEFAULT_TIMEOUT`, `PI`

! Packages
* **Convention**: lowercase, optionally separated by dots (.)
* **Example**: `com.example.project`, `org.apache.commons`

! Enumerations
* **Convention**: PascalCase for enum names and UPPER_CASE_WITH_UNDERSCORES for enum constants
* **Example**: 


```
  public enum Day {
      SUNDAY, MONDAY, TUESDAY, WEDNESDAY, THURSDAY, FRIDAY, SATURDAY
  }
```



! Annotations
* **Convention**: camelCase for annotation methods
* **Example**: 


```
@Override
@SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
```



! Type Parameters
* **Convention**: Single uppercase letter
* **Example**: `T` for type, `E` for element, `K` for key, `V` for value
* **Example**:

```
public interface List<E> { ... }
public class HashMap<K, V> { ... }
```



! General Guidelines
* ''Be descriptive'': Names should clearly convey the purpose of the variable, method, class, etc.
* ''Avoid abbreviations'': Use full words instead of abbreviations to make the code more readable.
* ''Use meaningful names'': Ensure the name reflects its purpose or usage.
* ''Consistency'': Follow the same conventions throughout the project.

! Example
Hereâ€™s an example that applies these conventions:

```
package com.example.project;

public class CustomerService {
    
    private static final int MAX_RETRY_COUNT = 3;
    
    private String customerName;
    private int customerId;
    
    public CustomerService(String customerName, int customerId) {
        this.customerName = customerName;
        this.customerId = customerId;
    }
    
    public String getCustomerName() {
        return customerName;
    }
    
    public void setCustomerName(String customerName) {
        this.customerName = customerName;
    }
    
    public int getCustomerId() {
        return customerId;
    }
    
    public void setCustomerId(int customerId) {
        this.customerId = customerId;
    }
    
    public boolean isCustomerValid() {
        // Validation logic
        return true;
    }
}
```


By following these conventions, you help ensure that your code is consistent, easy to read, and maintainable.






"""Method 1: Naive Approach

    Step 1: Get the string.
    Step 2: Create a character array of the same length as of string.
    Step 3: Traverse over the string to copy character at the iâ€™th index of string to iâ€™th index in the array.
    Step 4: Return or perform the operation on the character array.
"""


```
    public static void main(String args[])
    {
        String str = "GeeksForGeeks";
  
        // Creating array of string length
        char[] ch = new char[str.length()];
  
        // Copy character by character into array
        for (int i = 0; i < str.length(); i++) {
            ch[i] = str.charAt(i);
        }
  
        // Printing content of array
        for (char c : ch) {
            System.out.println(c);
        }
    }
```

"""
Method 2: Using toCharArray() Method

    Step 1:Get the string.
    Step 2:Create a character array of same length as of string.
    Step 3:Store the array return by toCharArray() method.
    Step 4:Return or perform operation on character array.
"""


```
    public static void main(String args[])
    {
  
        String str = "GeeksForGeeks";
  
        // Creating array and Storing the array
        // returned by toCharArray()
        char[] ch = str.toCharArray();
  
        // Printing array
        for (char c : ch) {
            System.out.println(c);
        }
    }
```








A `PriorityQueue` in Java is a specialized type of queue where elements are ordered based on their priority. By default, the `PriorityQueue` orders elements according to their **natural ordering** (i.e., for numbers, smaller numbers have higher priority). You can also customize the order by providing a custom comparator when creating the queue.

!Key Points:
#''Min-Heap by Default'': The `PriorityQueue` in Java is implemented as a **min-heap**, meaning that the smallest (or "least") element will always be at the head of the queue. This is useful for algorithms where you need to repeatedly access the smallest element.
   
#''Dynamic Ordering'': The queue automatically reorders itself whenever elements are added or removed to maintain the heap property (the smallest element remains at the front).

#''Not Thread-Safe'': `PriorityQueue` is not synchronized, so if multiple threads are accessing it concurrently, you must handle synchronization externally.

#''No Null Elements'': `PriorityQueue` does not allow `null` elements because `null` is used as a sentinel in many operations.

#''Comparator Support'': You can specify a custom order for the queue by passing a `Comparator` to the constructor, allowing for use cases like a **max-heap** or custom sorting.

!Important Methods:
*''add(E e)'': Inserts the specified element into the queue.
*''offer(E e)'': Similar to `add`, but returns `false` if the queue doesn't allow the addition (rarely happens with `PriorityQueue`).
*''peek()'': Retrieves, but does not remove, the head of the queue (the smallest element). Returns `null` if the queue is empty.
*''poll()'': Retrieves and removes the head of the queue (the smallest element). Returns `null` if the queue is empty.
*''remove()'': Removes a single instance of the specified element from the queue, if it is present.
*''size()'': Returns the number of elements in the queue.
  
!Example Usage:

```java
import java.util.PriorityQueue;

public class PriorityQueueExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Create a PriorityQueue of integers (min-heap by default)
        PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();
        
        // Add elements to the queue
        pq.add(10);
        pq.add(20);
        pq.add(15);

        // Print the head of the queue
        System.out.println("Head of queue (smallest element): " + pq.peek());  // Output: 10

        // Remove the head of the queue (smallest element)
        System.out.println("Removed: " + pq.poll());  // Output: 10

        // Add a new element
        pq.add(5);

        // Print the current state of the queue
        while (!pq.isEmpty()) {
            System.out.println(pq.poll());  // Output: 5, 15, 20 (in order of smallest to largest)
        }
    }
}
```

!Explanation of Example:
#''Adding Elements'': The elements `10`, `20`, and `15` are added to the `PriorityQueue`. The queue will order them internally so that the smallest element (`10`) will always be at the front.
   
#''Peek'': The `peek()` method returns the smallest element (`10`) without removing it from the queue.

#''Poll'': The `poll()` method removes and returns the smallest element from the queue. After `poll()`, the queue reorganizes itself, ensuring the new smallest element is at the front.

#''Adding Another Element'': When `5` is added, it becomes the new smallest element, and it moves to the front of the queue.

!Custom Comparator Example:

If you want to create a ''max-heap'' instead of a min-heap, you can use a custom `Comparator` to reverse the natural order.

```java
import java.util.Collections;
import java.util.PriorityQueue;

public class MaxHeapExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Create a max-heap by passing a Comparator that reverses the natural order
        PriorityQueue<Integer> maxHeap = new PriorityQueue<>(Collections.reverseOrder());

        // Add elements
        maxHeap.add(10);
        maxHeap.add(20);
        maxHeap.add(15);

        // Polling now returns the largest element first
        while (!maxHeap.isEmpty()) {
            System.out.println(maxHeap.poll());  // Output: 20, 15, 10
        }
    }
}
```

!Real-World Use Cases:
#''Dijkstraâ€™s Shortest Path Algorithm'': `PriorityQueue` is often used in algorithms like Dijkstraâ€™s, where you need to repeatedly process the smallest element (e.g., the shortest known path to a node).
   
#''Task Scheduling'': In systems where tasks have priorities, a `PriorityQueue` can be used to process higher priority tasks first.

#''Load Balancing'': In scenarios like the supermarket till example (above), `PriorityQueue` can be used to assign tasks to the least-loaded resource (i.e., the till that will be available first). 

!Time Complexity:
*''Adding an element'': O(log n)
*''Polling an element'': O(log n)
*''Peeking at the head'': O(1)

These efficient operations make `PriorityQueue` very useful for managing dynamically ordered data.






When structuring a Java project in Eclipse that uses Selenium and Cucumber, it's important to organize your directories in a way that makes the project maintainable and scalable. Here are some best practices for setting up the directory structure:

! Directory Structure

```plaintext
src/
â”œâ”€â”€ main/
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ java/
â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ PackageName(below)
â”‚   â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ Common/            # Java files (Functions.java, HabuAPI.java, Functions.java)
â”‚   â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ config/            # Configuration files (e.g., WebDriver setup)
â”‚   â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ pages/             # Page Object Model classes
â”‚   â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ utils/             # Utility classes (e.g., helpers, constants)
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ resources/
â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ config/                # External configuration files (e.g., .properties, .yaml)
â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ testdata/              # Test data files (e.g., CSV, JSON, Excel)
â”‚       â””â”€â”€ logs/                  # Log output files
â”‚       â””â”€â”€ files/                  # General Files
â””â”€â”€ test/
    â”œâ”€â”€ java/
    â”‚   â””â”€â”€ PackageName(below)
    â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ stepdefs/          # Step definition classes
    â”‚       â””â”€â”€ hooks/             # Cucumber hooks (e.g., setup and teardown methods)
    â”‚       â””â”€â”€ runners/           # Cucumber runner classes
    â””â”€â”€ resources/
        â”œâ”€â”€ features/              # Cucumber feature files
        â”œâ”€â”€ screenshots/           # Screenshot captures for failed tests
        â””â”€â”€ reports/               # Test reports (e.g., HTML, JSON)

```

!!Explanation:
*''src/main/java'': Contains the main application code.
**''config/'': Contains configuration-related classes, like WebDriver setup.
**''pages/'': Implements the Page Object Model (POM) for different web pages.
**''utils/'': Contains utility classes that provide common functions (e.g., file reading, date handling).

  
*''src/main/resources'': Holds non-code resources needed by the application.
**''config/'': Configuration files like `.properties` or `.yaml`.
**''testdata/'': Any external files used for feeding data to the tests.
**''logs/'': Directory for log output files.
**''files/'': General files

*''src/test/java'': Contains test-specific code.
**''stepdefs/'': Implements the steps defined in the feature files.
**''runners/'': Contains the Cucumber runner classes that define how the tests should be executed.
**''hooks/'': Contains Cucumber hooks, like `@Before` and `@After` methods.

*''src/test/resources'': Holds test-specific resources.
**''features/'': Contains the Cucumber feature files that define the test scenarios.
**''screenshots/'': Stores screenshots captured during test execution, particularly useful for failed tests.
**''reports/'': Stores test reports generated after the execution of the tests.

!Automating Directory Creation
You can automate the creation of this directory structure by using a script or a Maven archetype.

!!Using a Bash Script (Linux/MacOS)
```bash
mkdir -p src/main/java/your/package/name/{config,pages,utils}
mkdir -p src/main/resources/{config,testdata,logs,files}
mkdir -p src/test/java/your/package/name/{stepdefs,runners,hooks}
mkdir -p src/test/resources/{features,screenshots,reports}
```

!!Using a Batch Script (Windows)
```batch
mkdir src\main\java\your\package\name\config
mkdir src\main\java\your\package\name\pages
mkdir src\main\java\your\package\name\utils
mkdir src\main\resources\config
mkdir src\main\resources\testdata
mkdir src\main\resources\logs
mkdir src\main\resources\files
mkdir src\test\java\your\package\name\stepdefs
mkdir src\test\java\your\package\name\runners
mkdir src\test\java\your\package\name\hooks
mkdir src\test\resources\features
mkdir src\test\resources\screenshots
mkdir src\test\resources\reports
```

!!Additional Considerations
*Version Control: Make sure to include your directory structure in version control (e.g., Git).
*Build Tools: Consider using Maven or Gradle for managing dependencies, building, and running tests.
*Documentation: Keep documentation files in a separate directory, typically under `docs/`.

This structure helps maintain a clean and organized codebase, making it easier to manage and scale as your project grows.






!! java.util.Properties

`java.util.Properties` is a class in Java that represents a persistent set of properties. These properties are key-value pairs, where both the key and the value are `String` objects. The `Properties` class is a subclass of `Hashtable`, so it inherits all the methods from `Hashtable`, but it is specifically designed to handle property lists, which are typically used for configuration settings.

!!! Common Uses of `java.util.Properties`:
* '''Configuration Files:'''
  ** The `Properties` class is often used to load configuration settings from files with a `.properties` extension. These files contain key-value pairs, with each key-value pair on a new line, separated by an equals sign (`=`) or a colon (`:`).
  ** Example `.properties` file:

```
  username=admin
  password=secret
  db.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb
```
  ** You can load these properties into a `Properties` object using the `load()` method.

* '''Storing Application Settings:'''
  ** `Properties` can be used to store settings or preferences that need to be preserved across different runs of an application.

* '''Environment Variables:'''
  ** Although less common, `Properties` can also be used to manage environment variables within an application.

!! Key Methods in `java.util.Properties`:
* '''`load(InputStream inStream)` / `load(Reader reader)`''' 
  ** Loads properties from a given input stream or reader.
  ** Example:
  ```
  Properties properties = new Properties();
  try (InputStream input = new FileInputStream("config.properties")) {
      properties.load(input);
  }
```

* '''`getProperty(String key)`''' 
  ** Retrieves the value associated with the specified key.
  ** Example:
  ```
  String username = properties.getProperty("username");
```

* '''`getProperty(String key, String defaultValue)`''' 
  ** Retrieves the value associated with the specified key, or returns a default value if the key is not found.
  ** Example:
  ```
  String username = properties.getProperty("username", "defaultUser");
```

* '''`setProperty(String key, String value)`''' 
  ** Sets a property with the specified key and value.
  **Example:
  ```
  properties.setProperty("username", "newUser");
```

* '''`store(OutputStream out, String comments)` / `store(Writer writer, String comments)`''' 
  **Saves the properties to a file, with optional comments.
  **Example:
  ```
  try (OutputStream output = new FileOutputStream("config.properties")) {
      properties.store(output, "User settings");
  }
```

!! Example Usage:

```java
import java.io.*;
import java.util.Properties;

public class ConfigExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Properties properties = new Properties();

        // Load properties from a file
        try (InputStream input = new FileInputStream("config.properties")) {
            properties.load(input);
        } catch (IOException ex) {
            ex.printStackTrace();
        }

        // Access a property
        String username = properties.getProperty("username");
        String password = properties.getProperty("password");

        System.out.println("Username: " + username);
        System.out.println("Password: " + password);

        // Set a property and save it back to the file
        properties.setProperty("username", "newAdmin");

        try (OutputStream output = new FileOutputStream("config.properties")) {
            properties.store(output, "Updated settings");
        } catch (IOException ex) {
            ex.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

!! Summary:
`java.util.Properties` is a utility class that makes it easy to manage configuration settings in Java applications, allowing you to load, modify, and store key-value pairs in a simple and effective manner.







"""Declaring a method often starts with, where no data is taken in (hence the open/close parenthesis
`public static void methodName() {`

''public'': accessible by the outside world
''void'': no data is returned by the method; this is replaced by the datatype (int, String...) being returned if there is a return statement in the method.
''static'': can be called directly using the class name







When setting up a project that will be pulling data from an external file, setup a method in a Class. For the project I was working on, the Class was Functions and it was stored in the common package in src/main/java.
The external file being called was habu.properties and stored in the root project directory.



```
	public static String getProperty(String key) {
		String path = System.getProperty("user.dir") + "/habu.properties";

		File configFile = new File(path);

		try {
			if (!configFile.exists())
				throw new FileNotFoundException("File: " + path + "NOT FOUND");
		} catch (Exception e) {
			System.out.println(e.getMessage());
		}
		
		Properties prop = new Properties();
		
		try {
			FileInputStream fs = new FileInputStream(configFile);
			prop.load(fs);
		} catch (Exception e) {
			System.out.println(e.getMessage());
		}
		
		String value = prop.getProperty(key);
		// Assert.assertNotNull("Property" + key + "Lookup");
		return value;
	}
```

Other Classes (in the same package) would call the function by using

```
Functions.getProperty("AttibuteNameInPropertiesFile")
```


An example of usage:


```
response = request.post(Functions.getProperty("tokenUrl"));
```

Where the properties file has the line:

```
tokenUrl = https://api.habu.com/v1/oauth/token
```

https://poi.apache.org/index.html api can be used to read microsoft document.


```
import java.io.FileInputStream;
import java.io.IOException;
import org.apache.poi.xssf.usermodel.XSSFCell;
import org.apache.poi.xssf.usermodel.XSSFRow;
import org.apache.poi.xssf.usermodel.XSSFSheet;
import org.apache.poi.xssf.usermodel.XSSFWorkbook;

public class ReadingDataFromExcel {

	public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
			
		FileInputStream file = new FileInputStream(System.getProperty("user.dir") + "/testdata/data.xlsx");
		
		XSSFWorkbook workbook = new XSSFWorkbook(file);
		
		XSSFSheet sheet = workbook.getSheet("Sheet1");
		//Or instead of the above, use getSheetAt and give the sheet number
		//XSSFSheet sheet = workbook.getSheetAt(1);
		
		int totalRows = sheet.getLastRowNum();  //Rows are counted from zero
		
		int totalCellsInRow = sheet.getRow(1).getLastCellNum(); //Checks the 2nd row; Cells are counted from one.
		
		System.out.println("Number of rows: " + totalRows);
		System.out.println("Number of columns: " + totalCellsInRow);
		
		// First for loop is for rows; notice that is uses <= (because count starts with 0)
		// While second for loop is for cells/columns; notice it uses < (because count starts with 1)
		for(int r = 0; r<= totalRows; r++) {
			XSSFRow currentRow = sheet.getRow(r);
			
			for(int c=0; c<totalCellsInRow; c++) {
				XSSFCell cell = currentRow.getCell(c);
				System.out.print(cell.toString() + "\t");  // Make tab delimited output
			}
			System.out.println();	//return line after full row is printed
		}
		
		workbook.close();
		file.close();
	}

}
```







!! Read a text file as String

    // Java Program to illustrate reading from text file
    // as string in Java
    package io;
    import java.nio.file.*;;
    public class ReadTextAsString
    {
      public static String readFileAsString(String fileName)throws Exception
      {
        String data = "";
        data = new String(Files.readAllBytes(Paths.get(fileName)));
        return data;
      }
      
      public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception
      {
        String data = readFileAsString("C:\\Users\\pankaj\\Desktop\\test.java");
        System.out.println(data);
      }
    }
```







!! Reading the whole file in a List
"""
Read all lines from a file. This method ensures that the file is closed when all bytes have been read or an I/O error, or other runtime exception, is thrown. Bytes from the file are decoded into characters using the specified charset.

"""

```
    public static List readAllLines(Path path,Charset cs)throws IOException
```

    \u000D followed by \u000A, CARRIAGE RETURN followed by LINE FEED
    \u000A, LINE FEED
    \u000D, CARRIAGE RETURN
```

    import java.nio.file.*;
    import java.io.*;
    public class ReadFileIntoList
    {
      public static List<String> readFileInList(String fileName)
      {
      
        List<String> lines = Collections.emptyList();
        try
        {
          lines =
           Files.readAllLines(Paths.get(fileName), StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
        }
      
        catch (IOException e)
        {
      
          // do something
          e.printStackTrace();
        }
        return lines;
      }
      public static void main(String[] args)
      {
        List l = readFileInList("C:\\Users\\pankaj\\Desktop\\test.java");
      
        Iterator<String> itr = l.iterator();
        while (itr.hasNext())
          System.out.println(itr.next());
      }
    }

Pulled from iLearn Java Code Clinic Exercise 1
Reading from 


```
package org.example;
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.FileReader;
import java.text.DateFormat;
import java.text.SimpleDateFormat;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Date;

public class ReadData {
    ArrayList<WeatherEntry> collectedData = new ArrayList<>();

    public void readData(String fileName) {
        DateFormat format = new SimpleDateFormat("yyyy_MM_dd HH:mm:ss"); //This is setup to exactly match the format on the external files.

        try {
            BufferedReader buf = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(fileName)); //Used to scan the external file line by line
            String line = null;
            String[] wordsArray;
            boolean skipFirstLine = true; //This is used in the while loop below to skip the first line since it has a header

            while (true) { //This section will continue to load data until the end of the file is reached.
                line = buf.readLine();
                if (skipFirstLine) { // skip data header
                    skipFirstLine = false;
                    continue;
                }
                if (line == null) {
                    break;
                } else {
                    wordsArray = line.split("\t"); //Specifies the delimiter on the external file is a TAB
                    WeatherEntry entry = new WeatherEntry();
                    entry.pressure = Float.valueOf(wordsArray[2]); //This specifies that it's in the 3rd column on the external file.
                    entry.humidity = Float.valueOf(wordsArray[4]); //This specifies that it's in the 5th column on the external file.
                    entry.when = format.parse(wordsArray[0]); //This specifies that it's in the 1st column on the external file.
                    collectedData.add(entry);
                }
            }
            buf.close();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
   }
}
```

https://www.baeldung.com/java-file-to-arraylist

"""
Several of the methods found in JavaReadFromFile can be used to pull the data from a file. The following is an example of writing that data to an ~ArrayList
"""

!!''Using ~FileReader''
"""
The most basic way of reading a file in Java is using ~FileReader. By definition, ~FileReader is a convenience class for reading stream of characters from a File.

There are multiple constructors available to initialize a ~FileReader:
"""

```
FileReader f = new FileReader(String filepath);
FileReader f = new FileReader(File f);
FileReader f = new FileReader(FileDescriptor fd);
```
"""
All of these constructors assume that the default character encoding and the default byte-buffer size are appropriate.

However, if we want to provide custom character encoding and byte buffer size, we can use ~InputStreamReader or ~FileInputStream.

In the following code, we'll demonstrate how to read lines from a file into an ~ArrayList, using ~FileReader:
"""


```
ArrayList<String> result = new ArrayList<>();

try (FileReader f = new FileReader(filename)) {
    StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer();
    while (f.ready()) {
        char c = (char) f.read();
        if (c == '\n') {
            result.add(sb.toString());
            sb = new StringBuffer();
        } else {
            sb.append(c);
        }
    }
    if (sb.length() > 0) {
        result.add(sb.toString());
    }
}       
return result;
```

!!''Using ~BufferedReader''
"""
Although ~FileReader is pretty easy to use, it's advisable to always wrap it with ~BufferedReader, when reading a file.

This is because ~BufferedReader uses a char buffer to simultaneously read multiple values from a character-input stream and hence reduces the number of read() calls made by the underlying ~FileStream.

Constructors for ~BufferedReader take Reader as input. Additionally, we can also provide buffer size in the constructors, but, for most use cases, the default size is large enough:
"""

```
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(filename));
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(filename), size);
```
"""
In addition to the inherited methods from the Reader class, ~BufferedReader also provides readLine() method, to read an entire line as a String:
"""

```
ArrayList<String> result = new ArrayList<>();

try (BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(filename))) {
    while (br.ready()) {
        result.add(br.readLine());
    }
}
```

!!''Using Scanner''
Another common way of reading files is through Scanner.

Scanner is a simple text scanner, used for parsing primitive types and strings, using regular expressions.

When reading files, Scanner is initialized using File or ~FileReader objects:


```
Scanner s = new Scanner(new File(filename));
Scanner s = new Scanner(new FileReader(filename));
```

Similar to ~BufferedReader, Scanner provides readLine() method to read an entire line. Additionally, it also provides a hasNext() method to indicate whether more values are available for reading or not:


```
ArrayList<String> result = new ArrayList<>();

try (Scanner s = new Scanner(new FileReader(filename))) {
    while (s.hasNext()) {
        result.add(s.nextLine());
    }
    return result;
}
```

Scanner breaks its input into tokens using a delimiter, default delimiter being whitespace. These tokens can be converted into values of different types, by using various next (nextInt, nextLong, etc) methods available:


```
ArrayList<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();

try (Scanner s = new Scanner(new FileReader(filename))) {
    while (s.hasNext()) {
        result.add(s.nextInt());
    }
    return result;
}
```

!!''Using Files.readAllLines''
Probably the easiest way to read a file, and parse all its lines into an ~ArrayList, is to use the readAllLines() method available in Files class:


```
List<String> result = Files.readAllLines(Paths.get(filename));
```

This method can also take a charset parameter, to read as per a specific character encoding:


```
Charset charset = Charset.forName("ISO-8859-1");
List<String> result = Files.readAllLines(Paths.get(filename), charset);
```

X > 100 || X < 0        //OR statement
X > 100 && Y < 0    //AND statement
```

            int finalScore = score + (levelCompleted * bonus);
            finalScore += 2000;
            return finalScore;
        } else {
            return -1;
        }
    }

The following worked for sending keystrokes to a Selenium controlled browser where an Action method didn't.


```
import java.awt.Robot;
import java.awt.event.KeyEvent;

public class ZoomOutExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            // Create an instance of the Robot class
            Robot robot = new Robot();

            // Zoom out multiple times
            for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) { // Adjust the loop count for the desired zoom level
                // Press and hold the Control key
                robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL);

                // Press and release the Minus key
                robot.keyPress(KeyEvent.VK_MINUS);
                robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_MINUS);

                // Release the Control key
                robot.keyRelease(KeyEvent.VK_CONTROL);

                // Small delay between each zoom out action
                Thread.sleep(200);
            }
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

"""
A simple text scanner which can parse primitive types and strings using regular expressions.

I think it's generally better to use [[Java - BufferedReader]]
