Sets are used to store multiple items in a single variable.
Set is one of 4 built-in data types in Python used to store collections of data, the other 3 are List, Tuple, and Dictionary, all with different qualities and usage.
Sets use curly braces `{}`

A set is a collection which is ''unordered, unchangeable*, and unindexed''.

Duplicate values in a set will be ignored. If you want to create an empty set, you can't user the curly braces, you have to use the `set()` method.

```
thisset = {"apple", "banana", "cherry", "apple"}
print(thisset) #Output {'banana', 'apple', 'cherry'}

demo_set = set(("Bob", "Gene", "Bob", "Gail", "Teddy", "Gene"))
empty_set = set()
```

To add to an existing set, use the .add method. For example, if geo_out is an existing set and I wanted to add the return information from a call to the output_h3_id_attributes function, I would `add()` it.

```
geo_out.add(output_h3_id_attributes(h3_id_in))
```

Other methods related to sets

* `remove(elem)` - Remove element elem from the set. Raises KeyError if elm is not in set.
* `discard(elem)` - Remove element elem from the set if it is present
* `pop(elem)` - Remove and return an arbitrary element from the set. Raises KeyError if ...
* `clear(elem)` - Remove all elements from the set  

Joining two sets

*`union()` - example `new_set = demo_set1.union(demo_set2)`
*`update()` - this will add a set to another set. 
**ex. `demo_set1.update(demo_set2)` so now demo_set1 has both sets.

Keep only duplicates

*`intersection()` - Keep only the values that are the same between two sets and assign to new set. 
**ex. `new_set = demo_set1.intersection(demo_set2)`
*`intersection_update()` - keep only the values that are the same between two set and but have them stored in one of those existing sets.
** ex `demo_set1.intersection_update(demo_set2)` will store in demo_set1

Keep all excluding duplicates

*`symmetric_difference()` - removes duplicates between the two sets and keeps the other, assigns to new set.
*`symmetric_difference_update()` - similar to above only changes the value of one of the existing set instead of storing it in a new one.

Return set containing difference between two or more sets

*`difference()` -  removes duplicates between the two sets and keeps what remains from the FIRST set, assigns to new set.
**ex.  `new_set = demo_set1.difference(demo_set2)`, This will take all values from demo_set1 that are not on demo_set2 and save them to new_set
*`difference_update()`

Other

*`issubset()` - Returns a boolean. If all elements in the first set are present in the second set then it will return true
*`issuperset()` - 






!! ''Shallow Copies''
When dealing with nested information (lists in list in listâ€¦), if you make a copy of the original object, a change to one of the original objects inner lists will be reflected in both the original and the copy.

```
original = [['dogs', 'puppies'], ['cats', "kittens"]]
copied_version = original[:]
print(copied_version) #output [['dogs', 'puppies'], ['cats', 'kittens']]
print(copied_version is original) #output False
print(copied_version == original) #output True
original[0].append(["canines"])
print(original) #output [['dogs', 'puppies', ['canines']], ['cats', 'kittens']]
print("-------- Now look at the copied version -----------")
print(copied_version) #output [['dogs', 'puppies', ['canines']], ['cats', 'kittens']]
```


The copied_version list is a different object but the entries in it are pointed to the same objects that original is pointing to. So if you make a change to whatâ€™s in one of those â€œchildâ€ lists then it effects both original and copied_version.

[img[images/Python_shallow_copies.png]]

A way around this is to do an inner/outer copy:

```
original = [['dogs', 'puppies'], ['cats', "kittens"]]
copied_outer_list = []
for inner_list in original:
    copied_inner_list = inner_list[:]
    copied_outer_list.append(copied_inner_list)
print(copied_outer_list) #outputs [['dogs', 'puppies'], ['cats', 'kittens']]
original[0].append(["canines"])
print(original) #outputs [['dogs', 'puppies', ['canines']], ['cats', 'kittens']]
print("-------- Now look at the copied version -----------")
print(copied_outer_list) #outputs [['dogs', 'puppies'], ['cats', 'kittens']]
```



!! ''Deep Copies''
a deep copy (need to `import copy`) of a list not only makes a copy of the outer list, but also makes copies of all the inner lists. And their inner list all the way down. A deep copy is completely decoupled from the original.

In the below example, the â€˜Hi thereâ€™ on the original was not replicated on the shallow copy because it was appended to the top level of the original object, not in one of the inner lists.
The marsupials was added to the shallow copy but not the deep copy because the deep copy was used

```
import copy
original = [['canines', ['dogs', 'puppies']], ['felines', ['cats', 'kittens']]]
shallow_copy_version = original[:]
deeply_copied_version = copy.deepcopy(original)
original.append("Hi there")
original[0].append(["marsupials"])
print("-------- Original -----------")
print(original) #output [['canines', ['dogs', 'puppies'], ['marsupials']], ['felines', ['cats', 'kittens']], 'Hi there']
print("-------- deep copy -----------")
print(deeply_copied_version) #output [['canines', ['dogs', 'puppies']], ['felines', ['cats', 'kittens']]]
print("-------- shallow copy -----------")
print(shallow_copy_version) #output [['canines', ['dogs', 'puppies'], ['marsupials']], ['felines', ['cats', 'kittens']]]
```


Deep copies make their own full copy to different objects whereas shallow copies still point to the original inner objects

 [img[images/Python_deep_copies.png]]







"""Pulls elements from string/list/tuple. Uses same brackets as an Index but contains a colon was well.

It does not include the character in the last position (i.e. up to but not including). 
If the last number is over the length of the string then it just stops at the end of the existing string.
You can not include the first digit if you want from the start of the string (`[:3]`)
You can not include the last digit if you want to go to the end of the string (`[4:]`)
"""

```
julia = ('Julia', 'Roberts', 1967, 'Duplicity', 2009, 'Actress', 'Atlanta, Georgia')
print(len(julia)) #return 7
print(julia[2]) #output 1967
print(julia[2:6]) #Slice; return (1967, 'Duplicity', 2009, 'Actress')
print(julia[:5]) #Slice; return ('Julia', 'Roberts', 1967, 'Duplicity', 2009)
print(julia[4:]) #Slice; return (2009, 'Actress', 'Atlanta, Georgia')
julia = julia[:3] + ('Eat, Pray, Love', 2010) + julia[3:] #Append into tuple
print(julia) #return ('Julia', 'Roberts', 1967, 'Eat, Pray, Love', 2010, 'Duplicity', 2009, 'Actress', 'Atlanta, Georgia')
print(julia[:]) #returns the same as above...all objects in the list
```








Given a list of values, a quick way to find the smallest (minimum) or largest (maximum) value is to just use the `min()` or `max()` methods.


```
def minimum(arr):
    return min(arr)

def maximum(arr):
    return max(arr)
```

An alternative is to sort the list and then return the first or last element.


```
def min(arr):
    return sorted(arr)[0]

def max(arr):
    return sorted(arr)[-1]
```

!!! ''Sort Dictionary:''
Take a dictionary of Movies and their Rotten Tomatoes score; Output a list of the movies ordered by the RT score

```
rated_movies = {'Baby Mama': 64, 'The Five-Year Engagement': 63, 'Bachelorette': 56, 'The Heat': 65, 'Date Night': 67, 'Sherlock Holmes: A Game Of Shadows': 60, 'YahÅŸi BatÄ±': 0, 'Eyyvah Eyvah': 0, 'Pirates Of The Caribbean: On Stranger Tides': 32, 'Prince Of Persia: The Sands Of Time': 36}
```

You can use a function as a parameter to sort on. The `key` value must be a function. 

```
L1 = [-2, 4, 7, 1, 3]

def absolute(x):
    if x >= 0:
        return x
    else:
        return -x
#Using stand-alone function for sorting
sort_L1 = sorted(L1, key=absolute)
print(sort_L1) #output [1, -2, 3, 4, 7]

#Or use a lambda expression
sort2_L1 = sorted(L1, key=lambda x: absolute(x))
print(sort2_L1) #output [1, -2, 3, 4, 7]

#or in reverse order
print(sorted(L1, reverse=True, key = absolute)) #output [7, 4, 3, -2, 1]
```

or using `attrgetter` in conjunction with the `key`.


```
from operator import attrgetter

class Employee():
    def __init__(self, name, age, salary):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age
        self.salary = salary

    def __repr__(self):
        return f'{self.name}, {self.age}, {self.salary}'


e1 = Employee('Carl', 37, 70000)
e2 = Employee('Sarah', 29, 80000)
e3 = Employee('John', 43, 90000)

employee = [e1, e2, e3]
#Using attrgetter with key instead of lambda or a stand-alone function.
sorted_employee = sorted(employee, key = attrgetter('age'))
print(e1) # output Carl, 37, 70000
print(employee) # output [Carl, 37, 70000, Sarah, 29, 80000, John, 43, 90000]
print(sorted_employee) # output [Sarah, 29, 80000, Carl, 37, 70000, John, 43, 90000]
```








Uses function syntax vs the method syntax
With `sorted()` you get a value back whereas `.sort()` doesnâ€™t return a value, which is why on the last example below it returns None.
Invoking `sorted()` on a list doesnâ€™t change the list, it creates a new list in a different order.

```
list2 = ['cherry', 'apple', 'blueberry']
L3 = sorted(list2)
print(L3) #output ['apple', 'blueberry', 'cherry']
print(sorted(list2)) #output ['apple', 'blueberry', 'cherry']
print(list2) #output ['cherry', 'apple', 'blueberry']
print('----------')
list2.sort()
print(list2) #output ['apple', 'blueberry', 'cherry']
print(list2.sort()) #return None
```


This can also be used on types other than lists

```
print(sorted('Apple')) #output ['A', 'e', 'l', 'p', 'p']
```


You can use `.__getitem__` to pull the value of a dictionary item and use it in sorting as well.

```
inventory = ['Axe', 'Great Sword', 'Stick']
rarity = {
    'Great Sword': 98,
    'Golden Bow': 97,
    'Iron Sword': 80,
    'Axe': 34,
    'Stick': 1}
sort_inv = sorted(inventory, key=rarity.__getitem__, reverse = True)
print(sort_inv)
print(rarity.__getitem__('Stick'))
```

!! ''Reversing sort''
You can reverse a sort by providing an optional parameter (`reverse = True`)

```
list2 = ['cherry', 'apple', 'blueberry']
print(sorted(list2, reverse = True)) #output ['cherry', 'blueberry', 'apple']
```

You can automatically fill in a value from a list using the curly bracket and .format() method.

Ex. `print("Hello {}. Your score is {}.".format(name, score))`

```
scores = [("Rodney Dangerfield", -1), ("Marlon Brando", 1), ("You", 100)]
for person in scores:
    name = person[0]
    score = person[1]
    print("Hello {}. Your score is {}.".format(name, score))
    #Outputs lines like 'Hello Rodney Dangerfield. Your score is -1.' but for each element in the list
```

Or to take input an us it in a print
(note that below itâ€™s a calling for formatting the output to have 2 decimal places using the `:.2f`

Ex. `calculation = '${:.2f} discounted by {}% is ${:.2f}.'.format(origPrice, discount, newPrice)`

```
origPrice = float(input('Enter the original price: $'))
discount = float(input('Enter discount percentage: '))
newPrice = (1 - discount/100)*origPrice
calculation = '${:.2f} discounted by {}% is ${:.2f}.'.format(origPrice, discount, newPrice)
print(calculation)
```

If you want to have more readable output for very large numbers, you can use string format and denote to use comma separators

`print(f'{total:,'}`

Alternate way to use format is to start the string with f and put the variables in curly brackets inside the string.


`print(f'Amount must be between {MIN_BET} - {MAX_BET}.')`

`print(f'You are betting ${bet} on {lines} lines for a total of ${bet * lines}')`



!! round()
Alternative to using the `:.2f` when needing to output a rounded numeric is the `round()` function. A parameter you provide is how many decimal places you want to use. The issue though is if the decimals are all 0 then it will only use 1 whereas the format forces 2.

```
calculation = '${:.2f} discounted by {}% is ${:.2f}.'.format(origPrice, discount, newPrice)
calculation2 = '${} discounted by {}% is ${:.2f}.'.format(round(origPrice,2), discount, newPrice)
print(calculation) #Output $45.00 discounted by 22.0% is $35.10.
print(calculation2) #Output $45.0 discounted by 22.0% is $35.10.
```



You can also use the curly brackets inside a variable.

```
name = "Sally"
greeting = "Nice to meet you"
s = "Hello, {}. {}."

print(s.format(name,greeting)) # will print Hello, Sally. Nice to meet you.
print(s.format(greeting,name)) # will print Hello, Nice to meet you. Sally.
```


If braces (i.e. curly brackets) need to actually be in a string then use double braces

```
a = 5

print(setStr) #outputs The set is {5, 9}.
```







''Strings''

Can be contained in single or double quotes. If a string is going to be on multiple lines (or contains a single or double-quote within the string) then triple single (`'''`) or double (`"""`) quotes can be used.

Access a character in a string using the indexing operator:

!! len()
Length of string using len()

```
test_string = "Air Horn At The Beach   "

```


!! slice

```

```


!! .count()
Use `.count()` to fine the number of instances of something in a string

```
test_string = "Air Horn At The Beach   "

```


!! .index()
Use `.index()` to find the first occurrence of something in a string; if not found then returns exception; can be applied to strings, list and tuples; canâ€™t be used in conditional statement

```
test_string = "Air Horn At The Beach   "
print(test_string.index('H')) #return 4
```


!! .find()
Use `.find()` to find occurrence as well; if not found then returns -1; can only be applied to strings

```
test_string = "Air Horn At The Beach   "

```


!! .strip()
Remove/trim leading and trailing spaces with `.strip()`

```

```


!! .split()
Breaking up long strings into different pieces that are put in a list, use `.split('delimiter')`

```
test_string = "Air Horn At The Beach   "
splitted = test_string.split(' ')

```


!! eval()
Using the `eval()` function, you can dynamically evaluate arbitrary string-based or compiled-code-based input. 


```
def calculator(num1, operator, num2):
    if operator == '/' and num2 == 0:
        return '''Can't divide by 0!'''
    return eval('{} {} {}'.format(num1, operator, num2)) #eval takes the string and treats it a command (2+2 instead of '2+2')
```


!! .title()
This will take a string, capitalize the first character and lower-case all the following characters







"""
`.upper()` uppercase all characters in a string
`.lower()` lowercase all characters in a string
`.count()` count the number of instance of a character/string
`.strip()` remove whitespace from around string
`.replace()` replace all instance of a character/string within the string (see example below)
"""

```
ss = '    Hello, World    '
print(ss.upper()) #outputs upper but ss is not actually changed
tt = ss.lower() #lowercases value an assigns to tt
print(tt) #output     hello, world
print(ss) #output     Hello, World

els = ss.count('l') #result 3
print('***' + ss.strip() + '***') #output ***Hello, World***
news = ss.replace('o', '***') #result Hell***, W***rld
```

The below shows an instance where when calling the Paddle class, its also calling Turtle. So when you create an instance of Paddle it can use the Turtle methods.


```
from turtle import Turtle

PADDLE_WIDTH = 20
PADDLE_HEIGHT = 100
USER_PADDLE_X_POS = 350
NEW_PADDLE_Y_POS = 0
COMPUTER_PADDLE_X_POS = -350

class Paddle(Turtle): # Inheriting from Turtle
    def __init__(self, coordinates):
        super().__init__()
        self.hideturtle()
        self.shape("square")
        self.color("white")
        self.penup()
        # Default turtle size is 20x20 so these multipliers are used to end up with 20x100
        self.shapesize(stretch_wid=1, stretch_len=5)
        self.setheading(90)
        self.setposition(coordinates)
        self.showturtle()
```


And here is a main.py file calling paddle


```
from turtle import Turtle, Screen
from paddle import Paddle
from ball import Ball
from time import sleep

S_WIDTH = 800
S_HEIGHT = 600



screen = Screen()
screen.setup(width=S_WIDTH, height=S_HEIGHT)
screen.bgcolor("black")
screen.title("PONG")
screen.tracer(0) #This makes it so the information of the screen must be manually updated.

pencil = Turtle()


def draw_center_line():
    pencil.hideturtle()
    pencil.penup()
    pencil.pencolor("white")
    pencil.pensize(5)
    pencil.speed(1)
    pencil.goto(x=0,y=-(S_HEIGHT/2)-10)
    pencil.setheading(90)
    while pencil.ycor() < (S_HEIGHT/2):
        pencil.pendown()
        pencil.forward(30)
        pencil.penup()
        pencil.forward(30)

draw_center_line()
left_paddle = Paddle((-350, 0))
right_paddle = Paddle((350, 0))
ball = Ball()

screen.listen()
screen.onkey(right_paddle.go_up, "Up")
screen.onkey(right_paddle.go_down, "Down")
screen.onkey(left_paddle.go_up, "w")
screen.onkey(left_paddle.go_down, "s")

game_is_on = True
while game_is_on:
    screen.update()
    if (S_WIDTH/2 - 10 > ball.xcor() > -S_WIDTH/2 + 10
            and S_HEIGHT / 2 - 10 > ball.ycor() > -S_HEIGHT / 2 + 10):
        ball.ball_move()
        sleep(.005)
```







Swapping variables using Tuples

```
a = 1
b = 2
(a, b) = (b, a)
print(a, b) #output 2 1
```








A ''tuple'', like a list, is a sequence of items of any type. The printed representation of a tuple is a comma-separated sequence of values, enclosed in ''parentheses''. In other words, the representation is just like lists, except with parentheses () instead of square brackets [].

One way to create a tuple is to write an expression, enclosed in parentheses, that consists of multiple other expressions, separated by commas.


```
julia = ("Julia", "Roberts", 1967, "Duplicity", 2009, "Actress", "Atlanta, Georgia")
```

The key difference between lists and tuples is that a tuple is ''immutable'', meaning that its contents canâ€™t be changed after the tuple is created.

To create a tuple with only one element, you need to include a comma after that element Example: 

```
x = (100,)
```

!! .count()
Count the number of instance of something in a tuple

```
print(julia.count('Actress'))
```

!! index()
`.index()` can be applied to a tuple to find the first occurrence of something

```
julia = ("Julia", "Roberts", 1967, "Duplicity", 2009, "Actress", "Atlanta, Georgia")
print(julia.index(2009)) #output 4
```

!! .slice()

```
print(julia[2]) #output 1967
print(julia[2:6]) #Slice; return (1967, 'Duplicity', 2009, 'Actress')
print(julia[:5]) #Slice; return ('Julia', 'Roberts', 1967, 'Duplicity', 2009)
print(julia[4:]) #Slice; return (2009, 'Actress', 'Atlanta, Georgia')
```

!! Append value into Tuple
To append a value to a tuple, use slice to note the position, what it should enter, and then the rest of the tuple. 

```
julia = julia[:3] + ('Eat, Pray, Love', 2010) + julia[3:] #Append into tuple
print(julia) #return ('Julia', 'Roberts', 1967, 'Eat, Pray, Love', 2010, 'Duplicity', 2009, 'Actress', 'Atlanta, Georgia')
```








https://docs.python.org/3/library/turtle.html

Turtle is built-in drawing program.

Need to `import turtle` (or `from turtle import Turtle, Screen`)

To have the draw window remain after the drawing is complete, you import Screen, as shown above, but also need to include the lines at the end of the python code:


```
screen = Screen()
screen.exitonclick()
```







If setting up a project, like a game, if you want to have the screen manually update you'd use the combination of the screen class' `tracer `and `update` methods. The example below shows an instance where items are being drawn on a screen but you don't want to show the elements moving around, just their end positions.

Notice use of `screen.tracer(0)` when setting up the screen and then the `screen.update()` at the bottom.


```
from turtle import Turtle, Screen
from paddle import Paddle

S_WIDTH = 800
S_HEIGHT = 600

screen = Screen()
screen.setup(width=S_WIDTH, height=S_HEIGHT)
screen.bgcolor("black")
screen.title("PONG")
screen.tracer(0) #This makes it so the information of the screen must be manually updated.

pencil = Turtle()

def draw_center_line():
    pencil.hideturtle()
    pencil.penup()
    pencil.pencolor("white")
    pencil.pensize(5)
    pencil.speed('fastest')
    pencil.goto(x=0,y=-(S_HEIGHT/2)-10)
    pencil.setheading(90)
    while pencil.ycor() < (S_HEIGHT/2):
        pencil.pendown()
        pencil.forward(30)
        pencil.penup()
        pencil.forward(30)

draw_center_line()
paddle_right = Paddle("right")
paddle_left = Paddle("left")

def go_up():
    new_y = paddle_right.ycor() + 20
    paddle_right.goto(paddle_right.xcor(), new_y)

def go_down():
    new_y = paddle_right.ycor() - 20
    paddle_right.goto(paddle_right.xcor(), new_y)


screen.listen()
screen.onkey(go_up, "Up")
screen.onkey(go_down, "Down")

game_is_on = True
while game_is_on:
    screen.update()
```

"""
Sometimes, you may need to deal with text that includes characters that are not part of the standard English alphabet, such as Ã©, Ã¶, Ð¤, or Â¥. This is especially likely if you use REST APIs to fetch user-contributed content from social media sites like Twitter, Facebook, or flickr.

Pythonâ€™s strings are in ''unicode'', which allows for characters to be from a much larger alphabet, including more than 75,000 ideographic characters used in Chinese, Japanese, and Korean alphabets. Everything works fine inside Python, for operations like slicing and appending and concatenating strings and using .find() or the in operator.

Things only get tricky when you want to input strings into Python, or print them to an output window or write them to a file.

For output, your terminal (output) window will typically be set up to display characters only from a restricted set of languages (perhaps just English). If you issue a print statement on a string containing other characters, it may not display correctly in your terminal window. Indeed, you may get an error message. We will offer a workaround later on this page.

If you want to store unicode text in a file, you have to choose an â€œencodingâ€. This is analogous to the encoding of special characters in a URL string, but not the same. In a file, each unicode character has to be encoded as one or more â€œbytesâ€ for storage in a file. We have avoided low-level details about data encodings until now, but understanding a little about bits and bytes will help make sense of this.

A ''bit ''is a BInary digiT. It is a single value restricted to two (binary) possibilities, which we conventionally write as 0 or 1. Computers store bits as electrical charges (high or low voltage) or as magnetic polarities, or some other way that we need not be concerned about. A sequence of eight 0-1 bits is called a byte. For example: 01001000.

There are 2^^8^^=256 distinct eight-bit bytes. If we only had 256 possible letters in our alphabet, we could simply encode each letter as one of the available bytes. When we restrict ourselves to regular python strings, using only the ASCII alphabet (English, plus a few special characters), the encoding is that simple, so simple that we havenâ€™t had to think about it before.

When there are 75,000 possible characters, they canâ€™t all be encoded with a single byte, because there are only 256 distinct bytes (eight-bit sequences). There are many possible encodings. The one you will be most likely to encounter, using REST APIs, is called UTF-8. A single unicode character is mapped to a sequence of up to four bytes.

If you read in a UTF-8 encoded text, and get the contents using `.read()` or `.readlines()`, you will need to â€œdecodeâ€ the contents in order to turn it into a proper unicode string that you can read and use.

Fortunately, the requests module will normally handle this for us automatically. When we fetch a webpage that is in json format, the webpage will have a header called â€˜content-typeâ€™ that will say something like `application/json; charset=utf8`. If it specifies the utf8 character set in that way, the requests module will automatically decode the contents into unicode: `requests.get('that web page').text` will yield a string, with each of those sequences of one to four bytes coverted into a single character.

If, for some reason, you get json-formatted text that is utf-encoded but the requests module hasnâ€™t magically decoded it for you, the `json.loads()` function call can take care of the decoding for you. `loads()` takes an optional parameter, encoding. Its default value is â€˜utf-8â€™, so you donâ€™t need to specify it unless you think the text you have received was in some other encoding than â€˜utf-8â€™.

"""

''Note'': //You may see a u before the string in a Python 2.7 program indicating that itâ€™s a unicode string. In Python 3, all strings are unicode strings, so you shouldnâ€™t encounter any of those strange u characters in this textbook.//


Once you have python strings, everything will work fine until you try to print or write the contents to a file. If you print, and your terminal window is not set up to display that language, you may get a strange output, or an error message.

If you try to write to a file with unicode strings, you may get an error. When you write a unicode string to a file, Python tries to encode it in ASCII. If there is a non-ASCII character, the execution fails and raises an error that looks like this: `UnicodeEncodeError: 'ascii' codec can't encode character u'\xea' in position 1: ordinal not in range(128)`.

One solution is to use the Python method to encode the string, using a format such as utf-8. For example, `s.encode('utf-8')` will encode string `s` as `utf-8`. That will encode non-ASCII characters with multiple character sequences that are difficult for people to read but can decoded back into single Unicode characters. This is often the best way.

Another quick-and-dirty option, if you just have a few stray characters that are getting in your way, is to replace any non-ASCII characters with question marks. For example, `s.encode('ascii', 'replace')`. Of course, replacing characters with question marks destroys some of the information, but it may be helpful in some circumstances.

''Note'': //In the Runestone online environment, the `.encode()` and `.decode()` methods are not available for strings. You can only use them in a full python environment. In all of the cached data that we provide from REST APIs in this online book, we have tried to avoid Unicode encoding issues.//






Because Python runs C based code faster than Python based code, use the for loop instead of the while loop if possible.

Examples below return a sum from 0 to n.
Use:

```
def for_loop(n=100_000_000):
    s = 0
    for i in range(n):
        s += i
    return s
```
Instead of:

```
def while_loop(n=100_000_000):
    i = 0
    s = 0
    while i < n:
        s += i
        i += 1
    return s
```

When summing things, an alternative could be below and be even faster because sum does a for loop internally.

```
def sum_range(n=100_000_000):
    return sum(range(n))
```

Yet another way which is even faster is use numpy (which is a C function). Only disadvantage to this is that numpy creates an array in memory. So the below would create a 100M array whereas the methods above would not take up that much memory.

```
def sum_numpy(n=100_000_000):
    return numpy.sum(numpy.arange(n)
```










"""
You can reference a global variable in a function but you canâ€™t access a local (to a function) variable globally.
Good practice is to not reference global variables in side a function.
Below has a local Y and a global Y with different values. The definition will always try to use the local variable instead of the global (although you can force it to use the global, by specifying `global x` in the function,  but that is to be avoided)
"""

```
def square(x):
    #global y  #this forces the usage of the global Y but is to be avoided
    w = q + 1 #This is an instance of using a global variable in a function
    y = x * x #this is a local variable to the function
    return y
y = 5 #This is a global variable
q = 7
z = square(10)
print(y) #will output global variable 5
```

"""
For loops can be re-written as While loop.
For loop = ''definite iteration''
While loop = ''indefinite iteration''

The `continue` brings you back to the top of the `while` loop
The `break` take you totally out of the `while` loop
"""

```
x = 0
while x < 20:
    print('still running: ', x)
    x += 1
```
or

```
while True:
    guesses += 1
    user_guess = input("Make a guess: ")
    if user_guess.isdigit():
        user_guess = int(user_guess)
    else:
        print("Please type a number next time.")
        continue #Automatically brings you back to the top of the while loop

    if user_guess == random_number:
        print("You got it!")
        break #Breaks out of the While loop
    elif user_guess > random_number: #Use elif if you have more then 2 expected results; for this it would be 3 possible prints
        print("Guess lower")
    else:
        print("Guess larger")
```

```
def get_yes_or_no(message):
    valid_input = False
    while not valid_input:
        answer = input(message)
        answer = answer.upper()
        if answer == 'Y' or answer == 'N':
            valid_input = True
        else:
            print('Please enter Y for yes or N for no.')
    return answer

response = get_yes_or_no('Do you like lima beans? Y)es or N)o: ')
if response == 'Y':
    print('Great! They are very healthy.')
else:
    print('Too bad. If cooked right, they are quite tasty')
```

''Example of setting up a while loop to return the output of a different function.''

```
import random
import turtle

def isInScreen(w,t):
    """Determine if the current turtle position is within the area of the screen window created"""
    leftBound = - w.window_width() / 2
    rightBound = w.window_width() / 2
    topBound = w.window_height() / 2
    bottomBound = -w.window_height() / 2

    turtleX = t.xcor()
    turtleY = t.ycor()

    stillIn = True
    if turtleX > rightBound or turtleX < leftBound:
        stillIn = False
    if turtleY > topBound or turtleY < bottomBound:
        stillIn = False

    return stillIn

t = turtle.Turtle()
wn = turtle.Screen()
print('Window width: ', wn.window_width(), '  height: ', wn.window_height())
t.shape('turtle')
while isInScreen(wn,t):  #Calling function above to make sure icon is still on screen.
    coin = random.randrange(0, 2)
    if coin == 0:
        t.left(90)
    else:
        t.right(90)

    t.forward(50)
    print('Coordinates: ', int(t.xcor()), int(t.ycor()))

wn.exitonclick()
```

Allows pairing of sequences. You can then use the zip in conjunction with List Comprehension.
Zipped lists need to have the same number of elements. You can run it with a different numbers but it will ignore any values at the end of the lists which canâ€™t be paired.


```
L1 = [3, 4, 5]
L2 = [1, 2, 3]
L3 = []
L4 = list(zip(L1, L2)) #Creates a list of tuples
for (x1, x2) in L4:
    L3.append(x1 + x2)
#Alternate of the above L3, L4 and 'for' lines using List Comprehension
L3_alt = [x1 + x2 for (x1, x2) in list(zip(L1, L2))]

print(L4) #[(3, 1), (4, 2), (5, 3)]
print(L3) #output [4, 6, 8]
print(L3_alt) #output [4, 6, 8]
```

```
        print(name, eye_color) 
output:
tim blue
sally green
```

Doing CodeWars, I used the first code snippet for my answer to a question to sum a group of numbers that are not negative. 

```
def positive_sum(arr):
    sum = 0
    for i in arr:
        if i > 0:
            sum += i
    return sum
```

This was a much better alternative using list comprehension and sum (which automatically loops).

```
def positive_sum(arr):
    return sum(x for x in arr if x > 0)
```







Doing CodeWars, there was a problem where it would give a list of lists. Each small list would contain a bus stop with 2 integers, people getting on the bus and off the bus. The goal was to find the total number of people still on the bus after the last stop.

My original code was:


```
def number2(bus_stops):
    end_num = 0
    for i in bus_stops:
        end_num = end_num + i[0] - i[1]
    return end_num
```

But I found that the below was a much more concise form, using `sum `to iterate through the large list to get a total. 


```
def number(bus_stops):
    return sum(x[0]-x[1] for x in bus_stops)
```







Doing CodeWars, I used the following code snippet to address a question of finding the average of the values in an array, but return 0 if the array is empty


```
def find_average(numbers):
    if len(numbers) == 0:
        return 0
    return sum(numbers)/len(numbers)
```

Much better way was to use an `or` in the return. This also treats that reference to the incoming list as a boolean statement (`if array else`).


```
def find_average(numbers):
    return sum(numbers) / len(numbers) if numbers else 0
```







Codewars test was to get the sum of values between two given numbers (a & b). Clever method was to use a combination of `sum`, `range `and `min`/`max `functions.

`def get_sum(a,b):
    return sum(range(min(a, b), max(a, b) + 1))`

So given a, b of 5 & -1, the return value would be 14 (-1+0+1+2+3+4+5)






`metaclass=Singleton`


The ''metaclass ''parameter is used to define the metaclass of a class. A metaclass is a class of a class that defines how a class behaves.

The ''Singleton ''pattern ensures that a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access to it. This is often used when setting up a Logging utility to be used across all classes.

Hereâ€™s what it does:

*Creates a Single Instance: The Singleton metaclass checks if an instance of the class already exists. If it does, it returns that instance; otherwise, it creates a new one.
*Ensures Only One Instance: This is useful for classes that manage a shared resource or configuration and should only have one instance.

Here's a simple example:


```
class Singleton(type):
    _instances = {}

    def __call__(cls, *args, **kwargs):
        if cls not in cls._instances:
            cls._instances[cls] = super(Singleton, cls).__call__(*args, **kwargs)
        return cls._instances[cls]
```

When you use ''metaclass=Singleton'', it ensures that Utilities class only has one instance throughout the application.






To get a list with a range of numbers, use the range(a,b,s) function, where a and b are the start and end of the range and s is the step. The step is optional. Note that the last number is not included

Ex, using the for loop:

```
for number in range(1,10):
     print(number)
```


will output

```
1
2
3
4
5
6
7
8
9
```

Using the step:

```
for number in range(1,10, 3):
     print(number)
```

will output

```
1
3
5
7
9
```







When setting up a Python Selenium project, following best practices ensures maintainability, scalability, and reusability. Below are some best practices (Pulled from ChatGPT):

---

!! Use the Page Object Model (POM)
#POM helps organize elements by grouping them into separate classes representing web pages.

Example:

```
from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By

class LoginPage:
    def __init__(self, driver):
        self.driver = driver
        self.username_field = (By.ID, "username")
        self.password_field = (By.ID, "password")
        self.login_button = (By.ID, "loginBtn")

    def enter_username(self, username):
        self.driver.find_element(*self.username_field).send_keys(username)

    def enter_password(self, password):
        self.driver.find_element(*self.password_field).send_keys(password)

    def click_login(self):
        self.driver.find_element(*self.login_button).click()
```


This keeps element locators and interactions within a single page class.

---

!! Maintain a Separate BasePage Class
A BasePage class helps encapsulate common Selenium functions like clicking, entering text, waiting, etc.



```
from selenium.webdriver.support.ui import WebDriverWait
from selenium.webdriver.support import expected_conditions as EC

class BasePage:
    def __init__(self, driver):
        self.driver = driver

    def click_element(self, locator):
        WebDriverWait(self.driver, 10).until(EC.element_to_be_clickable(locator)).click()

    def enter_text(self, locator, text):
        WebDriverWait(self.driver, 10).until(EC.visibility_of_element_located(locator)).send_keys(text)
```

!!! BasePage usage:

```
from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By
from pages.base_page import BasePage

class LoginPage(BasePage):
    USERNAME_INPUT = (By.ID, "username")
    PASSWORD_INPUT = (By.ID, "password")
    LOGIN_BUTTON = (By.ID, "loginBtn")

    def enter_username(self, username):
        self.enter_text(self.USERNAME_INPUT, username)

    def enter_password(self, password):
        self.enter_text(self.PASSWORD_INPUT, password)

    def click_login(self):
        self.click(self.LOGIN_BUTTON)
```




---

!! Store Configurations Separately
Keep settings like URL, browser type, timeouts, and credentials in a **config file**.

Example: `config.py`

```
BASE_URL = "https://example.com"
BROWSER = "chrome"
TIMEOUT = 10
```

---

!!Use Fixtures for WebDriver Setup and Teardown
If using `pytest`, fixtures help initialize and close the browser properly.

Example: `conftest.py`

```
import pytest
from selenium import webdriver

@pytest.fixture(scope="function")
def driver():
    driver = webdriver.Chrome()  # Use WebDriverManager to manage drivers
    driver.maximize_window()
    yield driver
    driver.quit()
```
Now, each test automatically starts and stops the WebDriver.

---

!!Organize Tests Properly
Follow a structured directory format:

```
/MySeleniumProject
â”‚â”€â”€ /src
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ /main
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ /pages         <-- Contains BasePage & Page Object Classes
â”‚   â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ base_page.py    <-- Base Page
â”‚   â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ login_page.py   <-- Example Page Object
â”‚   â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ dashboard_page.py
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ /utils         <-- Utility methods (helpers, config readers, etc.)
â”‚   â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ config.py       <-- Loads .env variables
â”‚   â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ driver_manager.py <-- WebDriver setup
â”‚â”€â”€ /tests
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ /ui_tests         <-- UI Test Cases
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ test_login.py
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ test_dashboard.py
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ /api_tests        <-- API Test Cases (if applicable)
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ test_api.py
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ conftest.py       <-- Pytest Fixtures (WebDriver setup)
â”‚â”€â”€ .env                  <-- Stores sensitive credentials (not committed)
â”‚â”€â”€ .gitignore            <-- Ignore .env and unnecessary files
â”‚â”€â”€ pytest.ini            <-- Pytest configuration
â”‚â”€â”€ requirements.txt      <-- Dependencies
â”‚â”€â”€ README.md
```
*''tests/''â†’ Contains test cases.
*''pages/'' â†’ Stores Page Object Model (POM) classes.
*''utils/'' â†’ Contains utility functions, configs, or common helpers.

---

!!Use Explicit Waits Instead of time.sleep()
Avoid `time.sleep()`, and use explicit waits for better performance.

```
from selenium.webdriver.support.ui import WebDriverWait
from selenium.webdriver.support import expected_conditions as EC

wait = WebDriverWait(driver, 10)
element = wait.until(EC.presence_of_element_located((By.ID, "myElement")))
```

---

!!7. Parameterize Test Cases
Use ''pytest parameters'' to run tests with different data.

```
import pytest

@pytest.mark.parametrize("username, password", [
    ("user1", "pass1"),
    ("user2", "pass2")
])
def test_login(driver, username, password):
    login_page = LoginPage(driver)
    login_page.enter_username(username)
    login_page.enter_password(password)
    login_page.click_login()
```

---

!!Use WebDriverManager to Manage Drivers
Instead of manually downloading drivers, use `webdriver-manager`:

```
from selenium import webdriver
from webdriver_manager.chrome import ChromeDriverManager

driver = webdriver.Chrome(ChromeDriverManager().install())
```
Install it using:

```
pip install webdriver-manager
```

---

!!Conclusion
By implementing **Page Object Model**, **separating configurations**, **using fixtures**, and **structuring tests properly**, you create a scalable Selenium framework. These practices lead to **maintainable, reusable, and efficient** test automation.

```
bill_payer_alternative = random.choice(friends)
```













"""
Install steps for setting up Pi-Hole

Get image of OS from https://www.raspbian.org/
Get Raspberry Pi Imager; https://www.raspberrypi.org/%20downloads/
Install OS on SD card using imager
Eject and re-mount SD card
Drop blank ssh file and [[wpa_supplicant.conf|Raspberry - wpa_supplicant.conf]] file that has wifi connection info
SSH into Rasp Pi, default user is `pi` with password of `raspberry`.
Change default password using `passwd `command
Run `sudo apt update && sudo apt full-upgrade`
Run `sudo apt install realvnc-vnc-server realvnc-vnc-viewer`
Run `sudo raspi-config` to enable vnc, ssh, change network name....
Run `curl -sSL https://install.pi-hole.net | bash`
Take note that during the pi-hole install, there will be a line for Web Interface password. Take not of this.






The following is the text contained within a text file named wpa_supplicant.conf, to be placed in the root of SD card loaded to Raspbian OS'd raspberry pi.


```
ctrl_interface=DIR=/var/run/wpa_supplicant GROUP=netdev
update_config=1
country=US

network={
	ssid="wifiber2"
        scan_ssid=1
        psk="Cheesecake888"
        key_mgmt=WPA-PSK
}
```

''Characters''

|Character|Legend|Example|Sample Match|
|\d|Most engines: one digit from 0 to 9|file_\d\d|file_25|
|\d|.NET, Python 3: one Unicode digit in any script|file_\d\d|file_9à©©|
|\w|Most engines: "word character": ASCII letter, digit or underscore|\w-\w\w\w|A-b_1|
|\w|.Python 3: "word character": Unicode letter, ideogram, digit, or underscore|\w-\w\w\w|å­—-ã¾_Û³|

''Inline Modifiers''

|(?m)|Multiline mode (except Ruby and JS) ^ and $ match at the beginning and end of every line|(?m)1\r\n^2$\r\n^3$|1 2 3|
|(?m)|In Ruby: the same as (?s) in other engines, i.e. DOTALL mode, i.e. dot matches line breaks|(?m)From A.*to Z|From A to Z|
|(?x)|Free-Spacing Mode mode| (except JavaScript). Also known as comment mode or whitespace mode (?x) # this is a # comment abc # write on multiple # lines [ ]d # spaces must be # in brackets|abc d|
|(?n)|.NET, PCRE 10.30+: named capture only|Turns all (parentheses) into non-capture groups. To capture, use named groups.||
|(?d)|Java: Unix linebreaks only|The dot and the ^ and $ anchors are only affected by \n||
|(?^)|PCRE 10.32+: unset modifiers|Unsets ismnx modifiers|

"""Sample Data

Jennifer Martin-White
714-555-7405
217 High St., Old-town IA 82767
jenniferwhite@bogusemail.com
corey-321-schafer@my-work.net
https://www.google.com

''Search for only names''
`^[a-zA-Z]+\s[a-zA-Z-]+$`
This searches for beginning of line `^`. Followed by a string up text that can contain upper or lower case characters `[a-zA-Z]+` followed by a space `\s` followed by a string of upper or lower case characters or a dash `[a-zA-Z-]+` and the end of a line `$`

''Search for only phone numbers''
`^\d{3}.\d{3}.\d{4}$`
This searches for beginning of the line `^` . Followed by a group 3 digits `\d{3}`. Followed by an single character `.`. Followed by another group of 3 digits `\d{3}`. Followed by another single character `.`. Followed by a group of 4 digits `\d{4}`. Followed by the end of the line `$`.

''Search for email''
`[a-zA-Z0-9.-]+@[a-zA-Z0-9-]+\.(com|edu|net)`
This searches for any group a lower or upper case characters, numbers, dashes or periods `[a-zA-Z0-9.-]+`. Followed by an ampersand `@`. Followed by a group of upper or lowercase characters, numerics or a dash `[a-zA-Z0-9-]+`. Followed by a period `\.`. Followed by com, edu or net `(com|edu|net)`.

''Search for address''
`^\d+\s[a-zA-Z0-9.,' -]+\s[A-Z]{2}\s\d{5}$`
This searches for a beginning of line `^` then a group of digits `\d`. Followed by a space `\s`. Followed by a group of upper or lower cases alphas, or numerics, or single-quote or comma or period or space or a dash `[a-zA-Z0-9.,' -]+`. Followed by a space `\s`. Followed by a 2 Uppercase letters `[A-Z]{2}`. Followed by a space, followed by 5 digits `\d{5}` ending with a check for end of line `$`

''Search for URL''
`^https?://(www\.)?(\w+)(\.\w+)$`
This searches for beginning of line `^` then http. Since some addresses are secure and some aren't there might not be an s so we just check for a possible s `https?`. Followed by a search for double forward slashes `//`. Since not all URLs have the www, we search for a possible string like that but not required `(www\.)?`. Then a group of word characters `(\w+)`. Then a group that has a period and another group of word characters `(\.\w+)`. Followed by an end of line `$`.

''Search for only the core URL, like google.com.''
`[^https?://(www\.)?](\w+)(\.\w+)$`
or
`(\w+)(\.\w+)$`
This is based on the search string used in the ''Search for URL'' section. Remove the `^` because you will no longer have the string starting at the beginning of the line. Then add brackets around the http.... portion and include the caret character at the beginning to denote to exclude what's in the bracket from the search `[^https?://(www\.)?]`.

''Search for YYYYMMDD hh:mm:ss''
`^20[0-9]{2}(0[1-9]|1[0-2])(0[1-9]|[1-2][0-9]|3[0-1]) (2[0-3]|[01][0-9]):[0-5][0-9]:[0-5][0-9]$`
`^` designates start of line
`20[0-9]{2}` looking for years, starting with 20 and ending with 2 digits between 0-9 in each digit position
`(0[1-9]|1[0-2])` looking for Month. Either with a leading zero followed by 1 digit between 1-9 OR a leading 1 followed by 1 digit between 0-2
`(0[1-9]|[1-2][0-9]|3[0-1])` looking for day. Either with a leading zero followed by 1 digit between 1-9 OR one digit between 1-2 and another digit between 0-9 OR a leading 3 followed by a digit between 1-2
A space
`(2[0-3]|[01][0-9])` looking for hour. Either with a leading 2 followed by 1 digit between 0-3 OR a digit between 0-1 followed by another digit between 0-9
A colon `:`
`[0-5][0-9]` looking for minute. With a first digit between 0-5 and a second digit between 0-9
A colon `:`
`[0-5][0-9]` looking for second. With a first digit between 0-5 and a second digit between 0-9
`$` designates end of line






REST is a set of architectural principles attuned to the needs of lightweight web services and mobile applications. Because it's a set of guidelines, it leaves the implementation of these recommendations to developers.

Uses a ''URI ''(Uniform Resource Identifier)

When a request for data is sent to a REST API, itâ€™s usually done through hypertext transfer protocol (commonly referred to as HTTP). Once a request is received, APIs designed for REST (called RESTful APIs or RESTful web services) can return messages in a variety of formats: HTML, XML, plain text, and JSON. ''JSON is favored as a message format'' because it can be read by any programming language (despite the name), is human- and machine-readable, and is lightweight. In this way, RESTful APIs are more flexible and can be easier to set up.

An application is said to be RESTful if it follows 6 architectural guidelines. A RESTful application must have:

#A client-server architecture composed of clients, servers, and resources.
#Stateless client-server communication, meaning no client content is stored on the server between requests. Information about the sessionâ€™s state is instead held with the client.
#Cacheable data to eliminate the need for some client-server interactions.
#A uniform interface between components so that information is transferred in a standardized form instead of specific to an applicationâ€™s needs. This is described by Roy Fielding, the originator of REST, as â€œthe central feature that distinguishes the REST architectural style from other network-based styles.â€
#A layered system constraint, where client-server interactions can be mediated by hierarchical layers.
#''''Code on demand, allowing servers to extend the functionality of a client by transferring executable code (though also reducing visibility, making this an optional guideline).

|''Operation''|''Command''|''MethodProperty''|''Description''|
|Navigate to|driver.get(https://training.rcvacademy.com)|Method|Open the URL in browser session|
|Get Current URL|driver.current_uri|Property|read the current URL from the browser's address bar|
|Back|driver. back()|Method|Press the browser's back button|
|Forward|driver.forward()|Method|Press the browser's forward button|
|Refresh Page|driver. refresh()|Method|Refresh the current page|
|Get Page Title|driver.title|Property|read the current page title from the browser|
|Maximize Window|driver.maximize_window()|Method|Enlarges the window. For most operating systems, the window will fill the screen, without blocking the operating system's own menus and toolbars.|
|Minimize Window|driver.minimize_window()|Method|Minimizes the window of current browsing context. The exact behavior of this command is specific to individual window managers.|
|Full screen window|driver.fullscreen_window()|Method|Fills the entire screen, similar to pressing Fll in most browsers.|
|Closing a window or tab|driver.close()|Method|Close the current window|
|Quitting the browser at the end of a session|driver.quit()|Method|Close all the windows and tabs associated with that WebDriver session|







This is for a JAVA project, unsure if other languages are the same syntax. This includes a wait in it for 3 seconds to make sure the page loads.


```
WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(3));

WebElement body = wait.until(ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElementLocated(By.tagName("body")));
String bodyText = body.getText();

if(bodyText.contains("THANK YOU FOR SIGNING UP!")) {
	System.out.println("Submition successful");
} else {
	System.out.println("Something went wrong with submission");
}
```







selenium.common.exceptions.''ElementNotInteractableException'': ''Message: element not interactable'': This can occur because the element you specified in the page is not an actual element you can interact with, for example a button that you're trying to click. This is most likely an issue with you attempting to use an element identifier that is not unique to the page and it's attempting to use an instance higher up on the page (which is invisible). Attempt to change the element type or modify the one you have to specify the correct one.

''NoSuchElementException'': You've mis-entered the element identifier. (for example, the XPATH you gave is in an incorrect format)








Selenium's Expected Conditions are a set of pre-defined conditions that can be used with WebDriverWait to wait for specific events to occur before proceeding. These conditions help in synchronizing the automation process with the state of the web elements. Here are some of the commonly used expected conditions and their descriptions:


```
from selenium import webdriver
from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By
from selenium.webdriver.support.ui import WebDriverWait
from selenium.webdriver.support import expected_conditions as EC

driver = webdriver.Chrome(executable_path="path/to/chromedriver")
driver.get("https://example.com")

# Wait until the element with id 'example-id' is visible and clickable
element = WebDriverWait(driver, 10).until(EC.element_to_be_clickable((By.ID, "example-id")))

# Interact with the element
element.click()

driver.quit()
```



*presence_of_element_located(locator):
**Description: Waits until an element is present in the DOM of a page.
**Use Case: Useful when you want to ensure that an element exists in the DOM, regardless of its visibility.

*visibility_of_element_located(locator):
**Description: Waits until an element is present in the DOM and visible.
**Use Case: Useful when you want to interact with an element that must be both present and visible.

*element_to_be_clickable(locator):
**Description: Waits until an element is visible and enabled, making it clickable.
**Use Case: Useful for waiting until a button or link is clickable.

*text_to_be_present_in_element(locator, text_):
**Description: Waits until the specified text is present in the given element.
**Use Case: Useful when you need to ensure that an element contains a specific text.

*title_contains(title):
**Description: Waits until the page title contains the specified string.
**Use Case: Useful for verifying that the page has navigated to the expected title.

*title_is(title):
**Description: Waits until the page title matches the specified string.
**Use Case: Useful for verifying that the page has navigated to the exact expected title.

*alert_is_present():
**Description: Waits until an alert is present on the page.
**Use Case: Useful for handling alert dialogs.

*element_located_to_be_selected(locator):
**Description: Waits until the specified element is selected.
**Use Case: Useful for waiting until a checkbox or radio button is selected.

*element_located_selection_state_to_be(locator, is_selected):
**Description: Waits until the specified element's selected state matches the expected state.
**Use Case: Useful for verifying the selection state of checkboxes or radio buttons.

*element_to_be_selected(element):
**Description: Waits until the specified element is selected.
**Use Case: Similar to element_located_to_be_selected, but works with an already found element.

*invisibility_of_element_located(locator):
**Description: Waits until the specified element is no longer visible on the page.
**Use Case: Useful for waiting until an element is hidden or removed from the page.

*frame_to_be_available_and_switch_to_it(frame_reference):
**Description: Waits until the specified frame is available and switches to it.
**Use Case: Useful for switching to an iframe when it becomes available.

*staleness_of(element):
**Description: Waits until the specified element is no longer attached to the DOM.
**Use Case: Useful for ensuring that an element is removed from the DOM.

*element_attribute_to_include(locator, attribute, value):
**Description: Waits until the specified element's attribute contains the given value.
**Use Case: Useful for waiting until an element's attribute is updated to a specific value.

*url_contains(url):
**Description: Waits until the current URL contains the specified string.
**Use Case: Useful for verifying partial URL matches during navigation.

*url_to_be(url):
**Description: Waits until the current URL is exactly the specified string.
**Use Case: Useful for verifying exact URL matches during navigation.






I'm wondering if the below examples are for ''Python''. I've placed examples for Java further down

''NOTE'': the linkText and partialLinkText are referencing the text displayed on the page, not the text of the actual URL being linked to.

```
find_element(By.ID, "id")
find_element(By.NAME, "name")
find_element(By.XPATH, "xpath")
find_element(By.LINK_TEXT, "link text")
find_element(By.PARTIAL_LINK_TEXT, "partial link text")
find_element(By.TAG_NAME, "tag name")
find_element(By.CLASS_NAME, "class name")
find_element(By.CSS_SELECTOR, "css selector")
```


''Java'', using parenthesis instead of a comma. Also referencing driver.

```
WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();

driver.findElement(By.id("id"))
driver.findElement(By.name("name"))
driver.findElement(By.xpath("xpath"))
driver.findElement(By.linkText("link text"))
driver.findElement(By.partialLinkText("partial link text"))
driver.findElement(By.tagName("tag name"))
driver.findElement(By.className("class name"))
driver.findElement(By.cssSelector("css selector"))
```






findElement will return the location of one element on a page.

findElements is intended to return multiple locations on a page. The information is meant to be written to a List.

Example:


```
driver.get("https://cnn.com/");

// Maximize the browser window
driver.manage().window().maximize();

//  List the number of instances of a certain class on a page
List<WebElement> headerLinks = driver.findElements(By.className("header__nav-item-link"));
System.out.println("Number of header link items: " + headerLinks.size());
```







Below shows in JAVA how to 

#open a new tab
#get a list of the current tabs, 
#switch to one tab, 
#do something
#switch back to the first tab.



```
        WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();

        // Open a new tab by clicking a link
        ((JavascriptExecutor) driver).executeScript("window.open('https://cnn.com', '_blank');");

        // Get all window handles
        ArrayList<String> tabs = new ArrayList<>(driver.getWindowHandles());

        // Switch to the new tab
        driver.switchTo().window(tabs.get(1));
        System.out.println("Switched to new tab");

        // Perform actions in the new tab
        driver.findElement(By.id("someElement")).click();

        // Switch back to the original tab
        driver.switchTo().window(tabs.get(0));
        System.out.println("Switched back to original tab");
```

Code used to use webdriver manager so you donâ€™t need to keep downloading version specific browser drivers. The below is for Chrome. This also includes the Options functionality, and it specifies to not close the browser window at the end of the run. Just remove the Last â€˜fromâ€™ item, the first 2 lines of code and the options=options portion of the driver variable set.


```
from selenium import webdriver
from selenium.webdriver.chrome.service import Service as ChromeService
from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By
from webdriver_manager.chrome import ChromeDriverManager
from selenium.webdriver.chrome.options import Options

options = Options()
options.add_experimental_option('detach', True)
driver = webdriver.Chrome(service=ChromeService(ChromeDriverManager().install()), options=options)
```








There is a complete list of Exceptions in Selenium WebDriver mentioned in the Selenium Doc which you may or may not encounter in course of your testing. Hence in this article we will focus on some most common exceptions in Selenium WebDriver,

*ElementNotVisibleException: Although an element is present in the DOM, it is not visible (cannot be interacted with). E.g. Hidden Elements â€“ defined in HTML using type=â€hiddenâ€.
*ElementNotSelectableException: Although an element is present in the DOM, it may be disabled (cannot be clicked/selected).
*InvalidSelectorException: Selector used to find an element does not return a WebElement. Say XPath expression is used which is either syntactically invalid or does not select WebElement.
*NoSuchElementException: WebDriver is unable to identify the elements during run time, i.e. FindBy method canâ€™t find the element.
*NoSuchFrameException: WebDriver is switching to an invalid frame, which is not available.
*NoAlertPresentException: WebDriver is switching to an invalid alert, which is not available.
*NoSuchWindowException: WebDriver is switching to an invalid window, which is not available.
*StaleElementReferenceException: The referenced element is no longer present on the DOM page (reference to an element is now Stale). E.g. The Element belongs to a different frame than the current one OR the user has navigated away to another page.
*SessionNotFoundException: The WebDriver is performing the action immediately after â€˜quittingâ€™ the browser.
*TimeoutException: The command did not complete in enough time. E.g. the element didnâ€™t display in the specified time. Encountered when working with waits.
*WebDriverException: The WebDriver is performing the action immediately after â€˜closingâ€™ the browser.


One way to handle some of these in code individuals is:

```
from selenium.common.exceptions import NoSuchElementException, TimeoutException, StaleElementReferenceException

def handle_exceptions(action):
    try:
        action()
    except NoSuchElementException:
        print("Element not found!")
    except TimeoutException:
        print("Element not visible within the timeout!")
    except StaleElementReferenceException:
        print("Element reference is stale!")
    except AssertionError:
        print("Assertion failed!")
```

hey just thought I'd pass this selenium tip along if you didnt already know it. Since you mentioned you are testing in stage, if it ever comes up where you have to try to run your tests in a different enviornment and the locators that you used are not the same. You can include a pipe in your xpath like `"//*[example1]  |  //*[example2]"`

It will check for the presence of either element and if both are present I believe it just takes the first one






For finding the XPATH of a button that is nested down in the HTML, you need to designate a unique identifier to narrow down to a section and then given another unique identifier afterwards, separated by a single slash

In the example below is specifies the div node, then the attribute id = 'row2', followed by a single slash, followed by button note with an attribute name = 'Save'

`"//node[@attributename='attributevalue']/node[@attributename='attributevalue']"`

`driver.find_element(By.XPATH, "//div[@id='row2']/button[@name='Save']").click()`

[img[images/Selenium_XPATH_example1.png]]






There are multiple methods for sending scroll command. Some are using JavaScript and another is using the Java Actions class.



```
import org.openqa.selenium.By;
import org.openqa.selenium.JavascriptExecutor;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebElement;
import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.interactions.Actions;

public class ScrollExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.setProperty("webdriver.chrome.driver", "path/to/chromedriver");
        WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();
        driver.get("https://example.com");

        // Scroll by pixels
        JavascriptExecutor js = (JavascriptExecutor) driver;
        js.executeScript("window.scrollBy(0, 250)");

        // Scroll to the bottom of the page
        js.executeScript("window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight)");

        // Scroll to a specific element
        WebElement element = driver.findElement(By.id("element-id"));
        js.executeScript("arguments[0].scrollIntoView(true);", element);

        // Using Actions class to scroll to an element
        Actions actions = new Actions(driver);
        actions.moveToElement(element).perform();

        driver.quit();
    }
}
```

The place a wait in a Selenium Java script with no criteria:


```
WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(2));

// Put in a Wait to give browser an opportunity to load fully
try {
	wait.until((ExpectedCondition<Boolean>) driverWait -> false);
} catch (TimeoutException e) {
	// Expected timeout, do nothing
}
```







```
from selenium.webdriver.support.wait import WebDriverWait
from selenium.webdriver.support import expected_conditions as EC
```

```
wait = WebDriverWait(driver, 10)
```

Wait with no criteria:
[[Selenium - stand-alone wait]]


Element to be visible

```
wait.until(EC.visibility_of_element_located((By.XPATH, "//div[@id='monthWrapper']//tbody//td[@class!='inActiveTD' and @class!='inActiveTD weekend']")))
```

Clickable

```
wait.until(EC.element_to_be_clickable((By.ID, 'BE_flight_arrival_city'))).click()
```

Wait for a field to have a value (in this case blank)

```
wait.until(EC.text_to_be_present_in_element((By.ID, 'BE_flight_arrival_city'), ''))
```

Wait for a field to NOT have a value:

```
wait.until_not(EC.text_to_be_present_in_element((By.ID, 'BE_flight_arrival_city'), 'Mumbai'))
```

Wait until an element is visible before storing it's elements in a variable.

```
date_list = wait.until(EC.visibility_of_element_located((By.XPATH, "//div[@id='monthWrapper']//tbody//td[@class!='inActiveTD' and @class!='inActiveTD weekend']"))).find_elements(By.XPATH, "//div[@id='monthWrapper']//tbody//td[@class!='inActiveTD' and @class!='inActiveTD weekend']")
```

The above would be the replacement of the below, which doesn't have a wait:


```
date_list = driver.find_elements(By.XPATH, "//div[@id='monthWrapper']//tbody//td[@class!='inActiveTD' and @class!='inActiveTD weekend']")
```







DO NOT mix Implicit and Explicit waits in the same project.

!! Implicit waits 
can be specified inside the driver fixture (in the conftest.py file). Placing the following line right before the yield my_driver statement:

`my_driver.implicitly_wait(10)`

*Implicit wait tells the WebDriver maximum wait time when searching for elements before throwing Exception
*Implicit wait is global, it is applicable to all the webelements in the script
*Since Implicit wait applies to all webelements you ''do not'' specify "ExpectedConditions" on the element to be located


!! Explicit Wait
Will re-check for an element continuously until the element appears or the specified time passes before giving an Exception.

`WebDriverWait(driver, timeout=3).until(some_condition)`

*Explicit waits tell the WebDriver to halt the execution until a particular condition is met or the maximum time has passed
*Explicit wait time is applicable only to those webelements which are specified by the user
*Explicit wait requires the expected condition to be specified for elements, like "Wait Until Element Is Enabled "


```
import pytest
from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By
from selenium.webdriver.support.wait import WebDriverWait
from selenium.webdriver.support import expected_conditions as EC

class TestExceptions:

    @pytest.mark.waits
    def test_no_such_element_exception(self, driver):

        # Open page
        driver.get('https://practicetestautomation.com/practice-test-exceptions/')

        # Click Add button
        add_button_locator = driver.find_element(By.ID, "add_btn").click()

        wait = WebDriverWait(driver, 10)

        # the items after located are in double parenthesis because that function is looking for a tuple
        row_two_text_element = wait.until(EC.presence_of_element_located((By.XPATH, "//div[@id='row2']/input")))

        # Verify Row 2 input field is displayed
        assert row_two_text_element.is_displayed(), "Row 2 input should be displayed but is not"
```







While using Selenium (in Java), if you need to place a pause in the web commands, use the WebDriverWait function at the class level.


```
import org.openqa.selenium.support.ui.WebDriverWait;

public class MyClassName {

     WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(3));

     public static void main(String[] args) {
	try {
wait.until(ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElementLocated(By.xpath("/HTML[1]/BODY[1]/DIV[4]/ASIDE[1]/DIV[2]/DIV[1]/DIV[1]/DIV[1]/BUTTON[1]"))).click();
	} catch (Exception e) {
		System.out.println("Pop-up did not appear.");
	}
}
```







Project Structure (Hybrid framework with page object model)

*''Root'':
**conftest.py file is usually placed here
***Contain the webdriver code

*''Base'': This directory can contain base classes, modules, or utilities that provide common functionality or configurations for your test framework. For example, you can store a `base_test.py` module that defines a base test class with common setup and teardown methods.
**Base test classes: You can have a base_test.py module with a base test class that contains common setup and teardown methods that are shared by multiple test cases. This class can provide methods for initializing the browser, logging in, or performing other common test preparations.
***BaseDriver class would contain things like wait for presence of element or wait for element to be clickable.

**Base page classes: If you're using a page object pattern, you can have a base_page.py module with a base page class that encapsulates common page elements, actions, or verifications used across multiple page objects. This class can provide methods for interacting with navigation menus, performing common actions, or verifying page elements.

**Base utility functions: The "Base" directory can contain utility functions that are specific to your test framework or project and serve as foundational utilities. These functions might not necessarily fit into the broader categories of utilities you have in the "Utilities" directory. For example, you can have a base_utils.py module with functions for handling test environment setup, custom logging, or other core functionalities used by your tests.

*''Pages'': The "Pages" directory can hold page object classes or modules that represent the different pages or components of your application. Each page object can encapsulate the actions, elements, and behaviors related to a specific page or component. For example, you can have `login_page.py`, `home_page.py`, or `product_page.py` modules defining page object classes for respective pages.

*''Utilities'': This directory is suitable for storing utility modules or functions that provide reusable functionalities used across your test framework. It can include functions for handling common operations like logging, file operations, string manipulation, or generating test data. For example, you can have `logger.py`, `file_utils.py`, or `data_generator.py` modules inside the "Utilities" directory.

**Helper functions: This can include various helper functions that perform common tasks not tied specifically to the test framework's foundation. Examples could be functions for generating test data, manipulating strings, parsing configuration files, or handling file operations.

**Custom assertion functions: You can store custom assertion functions that provide additional verification capabilities beyond what's available in the base Python or testing libraries. These functions can encapsulate specific checks or verifications relevant to your project.

**Logging utilities: If you have specific logging requirements or customizations, you can store logging-related utilities in this directory. This might include functions for setting up logging configurations, formatting log messages, or providing log handlers tailored to your project's needs.

*''TestCases'': The "TestCases" directory is where you store your actual test case modules or files. Each test case module or file contains individual test cases using the pytest framework. For example, you can have `test_login.py`, `test_home.py`, or `test_product.py` modules representing different test cases or test suites.

*''ConfigFiles'': This directory can hold configuration files that provide settings or parameters for your test framework or application. It can include files such as `config.ini`, `settings.json`, or `environment_variables.py` containing configurations like URLs, credentials, timeouts, or other test-related settings.

*''TestData'': The "TestData" directory is where you store test data files or modules. These files can contain input data, expected results, or other data required for your test cases. For example, you can have login_data.json, product_data.csv, or test_data.py modules containing test data in various formats.

*''Screenshots'': This directory can be used to store screenshots captured during test execution, which can be helpful for debugging or reporting purposes. You can save screenshots with meaningful names to easily identify the context or failure. For example, you can save screenshots using names like failed_testcase1.png, exception_page.png, or checkout_error.png.

*''Reports'': The "Reports" directory is suitable for storing test execution reports or logs generated during test runs. This can include HTML reports, XML reports, or any other format that provides test execution results and statistics. You can save the reports with meaningful names and timestamps to keep track of test runs. For example, you can save reports as test_report_20220518.html, pytest_results.xml, or execution_log_20220518.txt.







strings and lists are different from the others because they are made up of smaller pieces. In the case of strings, they are made up of smaller strings each containing one character.

Types that are comprised of smaller pieces are called collection data types. Depending on what we are doing, we may want to treat a collection data type as a single entity (the whole), or we may want to access its parts. This ambiguity is useful

To run a script, type

```
>bash hello.sh
```


bash is needed because files, by default are not executable and need bash to execute
To make a file executable, use chmod.

```
chmod 755 hello.sh
```


Once done, to run the file without using the bash prefix, you must preface the file name with ./  The ./ is needed because the system searches the PATH for the way to execute something. The ./ notes to not check the PATH

```
>./hello.sh
```


Comments start with #

$0 is usually the name of the script, the path included
Then Parameters increment ($1, $2...)

```
>echo $?
```

"""
''Use the Unix find command to search for files''
To use the find command, at the Unix prompt, enter:
` find . -name "pattern" -print`
Replace `pattern `with a filename or matching expression, such as "*.txt". (Leave the double quotes in.)
''Options''
The general form of the command is:
 `find (starting directory) (matching criteria and actions)`
The find command will begin looking in the starting directory you specify and proceed to search through all accessible subdirectories. You may specify more than one starting directory for searching.
You have several options for matching criteria:
"""

|`-atime n`|File was accessed n days ago|
|`-mtime n`|File was modified n days ago|
|`-size n`|File is n blocks big (a block is 512 bytes)|
|`-type c`|Specifies file type: f=plain text, d=directory|
|`-fstype typ`|Specifies file system type: 4.2 or nfs|
|`-name nam`|The filename is nam|
|`-user usr`|The file's owner is usr|
|`-group grp`|The file's group owner is grp|
|`-perm p`|The file's access mode is p (where p is an integer)|
You can use + (plus) and - (minus) modifiers with the atime, mtime, and size criteria to increase their usefulness, for example:
|`-mtime +7`|Matches files modified more than seven days ago|
|`-atime -2`|Matches files accessed less than two days ago|
|`-size +100`|Matches files larger than 100 blocks (50KB)|

By default, multiple options are joined by "and". You may specify "or" with the -o flag and the use of grouped parentheses. To match all files modified more than 7 days ago and accessed more than 30 days ago, use:
` \( -mtime +7 -atime +30 \)`
To match all files modified more than 7 days ago or accessed more than 30 days ago, use:
` \( -mtime +7 -o -atime +30 \)`
You may specify "not" with an exclamation point. To match all files ending in .txt except the file notme.txt, use:
` \! -name notme.txt -name \*.txt`
You can specify the following actions for the list of files that the find command locates:

|`-print`|Display pathnames of matching files.|
|`-exec cmd`|Execute command cmd on a file.|
|`-ok cmd`|Prompt before executing the command cmd on a file.|
|`-mount`|(System V) Restrict to file system of starting directory.|
|`-xdev`|(BSD) Restrict to file system of starting directory.|
|`-prune`|(BSD) Don't descend into subdirectories.|
Executed commands must end with `\;` (a backslash and semi-colon) and may use `{}` (curly braces) as a placeholder for each file that the find command locates. For example, for a long listing of each file found, use:
` -exec ls -l {} \;`
Matching criteria and actions may appear in any order and are evaluated from left to right.
Full examples

* To find and report all C language source code files starting at the current directory, enter:
** `find . -name \*.c -print`
* To report all files starting in the directories /mydir1 and /mydir2 larger than 2,000 blocks (about 1,000KB) and that have not been accessed in over 30 days, enter:
** `find /mydir1 /mydir2 -size +2000 -atime +30 -print`
* To remove (with prompting) all files starting in the /mydir directory that have not been accessed in over 100 days, enter:
** `find /mydir -atime +100 -ok rm {} \;`
* To show a long listing starting in /mydir of files not modified in over 20 days or not accessed in over 40 days, enter:
** `find /mydir \(-mtime +20 -o -atime +40\) -exec ls -l {} \;`
* To list and remove all regular files named core starting in the directory /prog that are larger than 500KB, enter:
** `find /prog -type f -size +1000 -print -name core -exec rm {} \;`
"""
Note:
On some systems, the name of the starting directory must end with a / (slash), or the find command will return nothing. Thus, the starting directory in the previous example would be designated as /prog/, with a trailing slash. On other systems, a trailing slash does not affect the command. A trailing slash is never needed when searching in / (the root directory), . (the current directory), or .. (the parent directory).

From <https://kb.iu.edu/d/admm>

"""Navigating telnet use pwd to list you current directory. Use the following to change directory: cd /data/infadata8
Go to root directory: `CD /..` Go up a directory: CD..
From http://adminschoice.com/unix-commands-tutorial |* |The * wildcard character substitutes for one or more characters in a filename. For instance, to list all the files in your directory that end with .c, enter the command ls *.c| |? |? (question mark) serves as wildcard character for any one character in a filename. For instance, if you have files named prog1, prog2, prog3 , and prog3 in your directory, the Unix command: ls prog?|
"""

!! directory
|Change|`cd dir` Change to directory d|
|Make|`mkdir dir` Create new directory d|
|Move|`mv dir1 dir2` Rename directory d1 as d2|
|Remove|`rmdir dir` Remove directory d|


!! file	
|list , no details only names|`ls filename` , filename with wildcard character/s.|
|list , details|`ls -1 filename` , filename with wildcard character/s.|
|move to directory|`mv filename dirname` (wildcard character/s supported)|
|copy file to other/current directory|`cp file directory/newfile` or `cp directory/oldfile`|
|Delete the file|`rm file` , `rm -rf directory` - Recursively remove files & directly without any warning.|


!! File edit/create/view
